searched_papers [{'title': 'Global and Local Prompts Cooperation via Optimal Transport for Federated Learning', 'abstract': ' Abstract Prompt learning in pretrained visual-language models has shown remarkable flexibility across various downstream tasks. Leveraging its inherent lightweight nature, recent research attempted to integrate the powerful pretrained models into federated learning frameworks to simultaneously reduce communication costs and promote local training on insufficient data. Despite these efforts, current federated prompt learning methods lack specialized designs to systematically address severe data heterogeneities, e.g., data distribution with both label and feature shifts involved. To address this challenge, we present Federated Prompts Cooperation via Optimal Transport (FedOTP), which introduces efficient collaborative prompt learning strategies to capture diverse category traits on a per-client basis. Specifically, for each client, we learn a global prompt to extract consensus knowledge among clients, and a local prompt to capture client-specific category characteristics. Unbalanced Optimal Transport is then employed to align local visual features with these prompts, striking a balance between global consensus and local personalization. By relaxing one of the equality constraints, FedOTP enables prompts to focus solely on the core regions of image patches. Extensive experiments on datasets with various types of heterogeneities have demonstrated that our FedOTP outperforms the state-of-the-art methods. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['PromptFL: Let federated participants cooperatively learn prompts instead of models-federated learning in age of foundation model', 'Communication-efficient learning of deep networks from decentralized data', 'pFedPrompt: Learning Personalized Prompt for Vision-Language Models in Federated Learning', 'Learning transferable visual models from natural language supervision', 'Pre-train, prompt, and predict: A systematic survey of prompting methods in natural language processing', 'An algorithm for restricted least squares regression', 'On the translocation of masses', 'Reduce communication costs and preserve privacy: Prompt tuning method in federated learning', 'FedBN: Federated Learning on Non-IID Features via Local Batch Normalization', 'Efficient model personalization in federated learning via client-specific prompt generation', 'Model-contrastive federated learning'], '2 Related Work 2.1 Personalized Federated Learning': ['FedDisco: Federated Learning with Discrepancy-Aware Collaboration', 'FedTP: Federated Learning by Transformer Personalization', 'Federated learning from pre-trained models: A contrastive learning approach', 'Federated learning of a mixture of global and local models', 'Exploiting shared representations for personalized federated learning', 'FedBN: Federated Learning on Non-IID Features via Local Batch Normalization', 'FedBABU: Towards enhanced representation for federated image classification', 'Understanding convergence and generalization in federated learning through feature learning theory', 'Federated evaluation of on-device personalization', 'Federated optimization in heterogeneous networks', 'Personalized federated learning with feature alignment and classifier collaboration', 'Partialfed: Cross-domain personalized federated learning via partial initialization', 'Federated learning with personalization layers', 'Clustered federated learning: Model-agnostic distributed multitask optimization under privacy constraints'], '2 Related Work 2.2 Prompt-based Federated Learning': ['PromptFL: Let federated participants cooperatively learn prompts instead of models-federated learning in age of foundation model', 'pFedPrompt: Learning Personalized Prompt for Vision-Language Models in Federated Learning', 'Cross-domain federated adaptive prompt tuning for clip', 'Learning transferable visual models from natural language supervision', 'Conditional prompt learning for vision-language models', 'Reduce communication costs and preserve privacy: Prompt tuning method in federated learning', 'Efficient model personalization in federated learning via client-specific prompt generation', 'FedCLIP: Fast Generalization and Personalization for CLIP in Federated Learning', 'Learning Federated Visual Prompt in Null Space for MRI Reconstruction', 'Learning to prompt for vision-language models'], '2 Related Work 2.3 Optimal Transport': ['An optimal transport approach to personalized federated learning', 'Scaling algorithms for unbalanced optimal transport problems', 'Learning with a Wasserstein loss', 'Deepjdot: Deep joint distribution optimal transport for unsupervised domain adaptation', 'OT-Filter: An Optimal Transport Filter for Learning With Noisy Labels', 'Computing all optimal partial transports', 'On the translocation of masses', 'Diagonal equivalence to matrices with prescribed row and column sums', 'A Combinatorial Algorithm for Approximating the Optimal Transport in the Parallel and MPC Settings', 'Causal optimal transport for treatment effect estimation', 'Prompt learning with optimal transport for vision-language models', 'Sinkhorn distances: Lightspeed computation of optimal transport'], '3 Preliminaries 3.1 Prompt Learning': ['Learning to prompt for vision-language models', 'Learning transferable visual models from natural language supervision'], '3 Preliminaries 3.2 Optimal Transport': ['Sinkhorn distances: Lightspeed computation of optimal transport'], '4 Methodology 4.2 Global-Local Prompt Cooperation by Unbalanced Optimal Transport': ['CSOT: Curriculum and Structure-Aware Optimal Transport for Learning with Noisy Labels', 'Iterative bregman projections for regularized transportation problems', 'An algorithm for restricted least squares regression', 'Prompt learning with optimal transport for vision-language models'], '4 Methodology 4.3 Generalization Bound': ['PromptFL: Let federated participants cooperatively learn prompts instead of models-federated learning in age of foundation model'], '5 Experiments 5.1 Experimental Setup': ['Geodesic flow kernel for unsupervised domain adaptation', 'Automated flower classification over a large number of classes', 'Federated learning with personalization layers', 'Deep residual learning for image recognition', 'Learning to prompt for vision-language models', 'Personalized Cross-Silo Federated Learning on Non-IID Data', 'Personalized federated learning using hypernetworks', 'An image is worth 16x16 words: Transformers for image recognition at scale', 'Describing textures in the wild', 'Learning generative visual models from few training examples: An incremental bayesian approach tested on 101 object categories', 'Food-101–mining discriminative components with random forests', 'Learning transferable visual models from natural language supervision', 'Fine-tuning is Fine in Federated Learning', 'FedBN: Federated Learning on Non-IID Features via Local Batch Normalization', 'Federated optimization in heterogeneous networks', 'Cats and dogs', 'Learning multiple layers of features from tiny images', 'PromptFL: Let federated participants cooperatively learn prompts instead of models-federated learning in age of foundation model', 'pFedPrompt: Learning Personalized Prompt for Vision-Language Models in Federated Learning', 'Moment matching for multi-source domain adaptation'], '5 Experiments 5.2 Performance Evaluation': ['Cats and dogs', 'pFedPrompt: Learning Personalized Prompt for Vision-Language Models in Federated Learning'], '5 Experiments 5.3 Ablation Study': ['PromptFL: Let federated participants cooperatively learn prompts instead of models-federated learning in age of foundation model']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_3', '8808801416211653744']}, {'title': 'PeFLL: Personalized Federated Learning by Learning to Learn', 'abstract': ' Abstract We present PeFLL, a new personalized federated learning algorithm that improves over the state-of-the-art in three aspects: 1) it produces more accurate models, especially in the low-data regime, and not only for clients present during its training phase, but also for any that may emerge in the future; 2) it reduces the amount of on-client computation and client-server communication by providing future clients with ready-to-use personalized models that require no additional finetuning or optimization; 3) it comes with theoretical guarantees that establish generalization from the observed clients to future ones. At the core of PeFLL lies a learning-to-learn approach that jointly trains an embedding network and a hypernetwork. The embedding network is used to represent clients in a latent descriptor space in a way that reflects their similarity to each other. The hypernetwork takes as input such descriptors and outputs the parameters of fully personalized client models. In combination, both networks constitute a learning algorithm that achieves state-of-the-art performance in several personalized federated learning benchmarks. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['Federated learning: Challenges, methods, and future directions', 'Federated multi-task learning', 'Communication-efficient learning of deep networks from decentralized data', 'Federated learning for mobile keyboard prediction'], '2 Related Work': ['Learning to Learn', 'Personalized federated learning using hypernetworks', 'FedTP: Federated learning by transformer personalization', 'A PAC-Bayesian bound for lifelong learning', 'Layer-wised model aggregation for personalized federated learning', 'An efficient framework for clustered federated learning', 'A unified view on PAC-Bayes bounds for meta-learning', 'Hypernetworks', 'Personalized federated learning with theoretical guarantees: A model-agnostic meta-learning approach', 'A perspective view and survey of meta-learning', 'Federated multi-task learning', 'Continual Learning in Reinforcement Environments', 'A model of inductive bias learning', 'Lifelong robot learning', 'Federated learning with personalization layers'], '3 Method': ['A pragmatic introduction to secure multi-party computation', 'The algorithmic foundations of differential privacy', 'Deep sets'], '3 Method 3.1 Convergence Guarantees': ['Scaffold: Stochastic controlled averaging for federated learning'], '3 Method 3.2 Generalization Guarantees': ['A unified view on PAC-Bayes bounds for meta-learning', 'A model of inductive bias learning'], '4 Experiments Datasets': ['Learning multiple layers of features from tiny images', 'LEAF: A benchmark for federated settings'], '4 Experiments Baselines': ['Personalized federated learning with moreau envelopes', 'Personalized federated learning using hypernetworks', 'Communication-efficient learning of deep networks from decentralized data', 'Personalized federated learning through local memorization', 'Exploiting shared representations for personalized federated learning', 'Personalized federated learning with theoretical guarantees: A model-agnostic meta-learning approach', 'Model-agnostic meta-learning for fast adaptation of deep networks'], '4 Experiments Models': ['Gradient-based learning applied to document recognition'], '4 Experiments 4.1 Results': ['The proof and measurement of association between two things']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_3', '7991598684894070399']}, {'title': 'PAGE: Equilibrate Personalization and Generalization in Federated Learning', 'abstract': ' Abstract. Federated learning (FL) is becoming a major driving force behind machine learning as a service, where customers (clients) collaboratively benefit from shared local updates under the orchestration of the service provider (server). Representing clients’ current demands and the server’s future demand, local model personalization and global model generalization are separately investigated, as the ill-effects of data heterogeneity enforce the community to focus on one over the other. However, these two seemingly competing goals are of equal importance rather than black and white issues, and should be achieved simultaneously. In this paper, we propose the first algorithm to balance personalization and generalization on top of game theory, dubbed PAGE, which reshapes FL as a co-opetition game between clients and the server. To explore the equilibrium, PAGE further formulates the game as Markov decision processes, and leverages the reinforcement learning algorithm, which simplifies the solving complexity. Extensive experiments on four widespread datasets show that PAGE outperforms state-of-the-art FL baselines in terms of global and local prediction accuracy simultaneously, and the accuracy can be improved by up to 35.20% and 39.91%, respectively. In addition, biased variants of PAGE imply promising adaptiveness to demand shifts in practice. ', 'sections': {'1. Introduction': ['Billion-Scale Federated Learning on Mobile Clients: A Submodel Design with Tunable Privacy', 'Personalized Federated Learning with Moreau Envelopes', 'Handbook of Dynamic Game Theory', 'Continuous control with deep reinforcement learning', 'Towards Federated Learning at Scale: System Design', 'Federated learning: Strategies for improving communication efficiency', 'Communication-Efficient Learning of Deep Networks from Decentralized Data', 'A Markovian Decision Process', 'Towards Personalized Federated Learning', 'On the convergence of fedavg on non-iid data', 'On Bridging Generic and Personalized Federated Learning for Image Classification', 'Contribution-Aware Federated Learning for Smart Healthcare'], '2. Related Work': ['Personalized Federated Learning with Moreau Envelopes', 'Federated Optimization in Heterogeneous Networks', 'FedALA: Adaptive Local Aggregation for Personalized Federated Learning', 'Dap-FL: Federated Learning Flourishes by Adaptive Tuning and Secure Aggregation', 'Communication-Efficient Learning of Deep Networks from Decentralized Data', 'Federated Reconstruction: Partially Local Federated Learning', 'On the convergence of fedavg on non-iid data', 'SCAFFOLD: Stochastic Controlled Averaging for Federated Learning', 'On Bridging Generic and Personalized Federated Learning for Image Classification', 'Federated learning based on dynamic regularization', 'Ditto: Fair and Robust Federated Learning Through Personalization'], '3. Problem Statement': ['On Bridging Generic and Personalized Federated Learning for Image Classification'], '4. Proposed Method: PAGE 4.1. Game (Relation) Establishment': ['Handbook of Dynamic Game Theory', 'Dap-FL: Federated Learning Flourishes by Adaptive Tuning and Secure Aggregation'], '4. Proposed Method: PAGE 4.2. Strategy Exploration in the Server-level Sub-game': ['A Markovian Decision Process', 'Continuous control with deep reinforcement learning', 'Handbook of Dynamic Game Theory'], '4. Proposed Method: PAGE 4.4. Workflow of PAGE': ['Deep Reinforcement Learning: A Brief Survey'], '4. Proposed Method: PAGE 4.5. Theoretical Analysis for the Equilibrium': ['Handbook of Dynamic Game Theory'], '5. Experiments and Evaluation 5.1. Experimental Settings': ['Learning multiple layers of features from tiny images', 'Tiny imagenet visual recognition challenge', 'Personalized Federated Learning with Moreau Envelopes', 'Federated Optimization in Heterogeneous Networks', 'FedALA: Adaptive Local Aggregation for Personalized Federated Learning', 'Long Short-Term Memory', 'Dap-FL: Federated Learning Flourishes by Adaptive Tuning and Secure Aggregation', 'LEAF: A Benchmark for Federated Settings', 'Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition', 'Communication-Efficient Learning of Deep Networks from Decentralized Data', 'Federated Reconstruction: Partially Local Federated Learning', 'Towards Personalized Federated Learning', 'On Bridging Generic and Personalized Federated Learning for Image Classification', 'SCAFFOLD: Stochastic Controlled Averaging for Federated Learning', 'Federated learning based on dynamic regularization', 'Ditto: Fair and Robust Federated Learning Through Personalization'], '5. Experiments and Evaluation 5.2. Results and Evaluation': ['Salvaging federated learning by local adaptation', 'Towards Fair and Privacy-Preserving Federated Deep Models', 'FedLab: A Flexible Federated Learning Framework']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_0', '1499358865230091895']}]
searched_papers [{'title': 'Zero-shot Referring Expression Comprehension via Structural Similarity Between Images and Captions', 'abstract': ' Abstract Zero-shot referring expression comprehension aims at localizing bounding boxes in an image corresponding to provided textual prompts, which requires: (i) a fine-grained disentanglement of complex visual scene and textual context, and (ii) a capacity to understand relationships among disentangled entities. Unfortunately, existing large vision-language alignment (VLA) models, e.g., CLIP, struggle with both aspects so cannot be directly used for this task. To mitigate this gap, we leverage large foundation models to disentangle both images and texts into triplets in the format of (subject,predicate,object)subjectpredicateobject(\\texttt{subject},\\texttt{predicate},\\texttt{object}). After that, grounding is accomplished by calculating the structural similarity matrix between visual and textual triplets with a VLA model, and subsequently propagate it to an instance-level similarity matrix. Furthermore, to equip VLA models with the ability of relationship understanding, we design a triplet-matching objective to fine-tune the VLA models on a collection of curated dataset containing abundant entity relationships. Experiments demonstrate that our visual grounding performance increase of up to 19.5% over the SOTA zero-shot model on RefCOCO/+/g. On the more challenging Who’s Waldo dataset, our zero-shot approach achieves comparable accuracy to the fully supervised model. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['Referring relationships', 'Dense and aligned captions (dac) promote compositional reasoning in vl models', 'Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Vision-and-language navigation: A survey of tasks, methods, and future directions', 'Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Learning transferable visual models from natural language supervision', 'When and why vision-language models behave like bags-of-words, and what to do about it?', 'Comclip: Training-free compositional image and text matching', 'Hico: A benchmark for recognizing human-object interactions in images', 'Structure-clip: Enhance multi-modal language representations with structure knowledge', 'Visual genome: Connecting language and vision using crowdsourced dense image annotations', 'Aligning bag of regions for open-vocabulary object detection', 'Ok-vqa: A visual question answering benchmark requiring external knowledge', 'Flava: A foundational language and vision alignment model', 'Generation and comprehension of unambiguous object descriptions', 'Gentopia: A collaborative platform for tool-augmented llms', 'A comprehensive survey of deep learning for image captioning'], '2 Related Work': ['Objects365: A large-scale, high-quality dataset for object detection', 'Dense and aligned captions (dac) promote compositional reasoning in vl models', 'Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Higher-order coreference resolution with coarse-to-fine inference', 'Flickr30k entities: Collecting region-to-phrase correspondences for richer image-to-sentence models', 'Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Incorporating structured representations into pretrained vision & language models using scene graphs', 'Simple bert models for relation extraction and semantic role labeling', 'Microsoft coco: Common objects in context', 'Hico: A benchmark for recognizing human-object interactions in images', 'Glipv2: Unifying localization and vision-language understanding', 'Visual genome: Connecting language and vision using crowdsourced dense image annotations', 'Nested named entity recognition', 'Refining event extraction through cross-document inference', 'Position-aware attention and supervised data improve slot filling', 'Deep semantic role labeling: What works and what’s next', 'Generation and comprehension of unambiguous object descriptions', 'When and why vision-language models behave like bags-of-words, and what to do about it?'], '3 Proposed Approach 3.1 Constructing Triplets': ['Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension'], '3 Proposed Approach 3.2 Grounding Based on the Structural Similarity': ['Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Generation and comprehension of unambiguous object descriptions'], '3 Proposed Approach 3.3 Enhanced Relational Understanding': ['Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Hico: A benchmark for recognizing human-object interactions in images', 'Grounded situation recognition', 'Visual genome: Connecting language and vision using crowdsourced dense image annotations', 'Dense and aligned captions (dac) promote compositional reasoning in vl models'], '4 Experiments 4.1 Setup': ['Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Microsoft coco: Common objects in context', 'Modeling context in referring expressions', 'Generation and comprehension of unambiguous object descriptions'], '4 Experiments 4.2 Implementation Details': ['Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Teaching structured vision & language concepts to vision & language models', 'Grounded situation recognition', 'Mattnet: Modular attention network for referring expression comprehension', 'Peft: State-of-the-art parameter-efficient fine-tuning methods'], '4 Experiments 4.3 Main Results': ['Grad-cam: Visual explanations from deep networks via gradient-based localization', 'Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Cpt: Colorful prompt tuning for pre-trained vision-language models', 'Consnet: Learning consistency graph for zero-shot human-object interaction detection', 'Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Mattnet: Modular attention network for referring expression comprehension', 'Contrastive learning for weakly supervised phrase grounding', 'Uniter: Universal image-text representation learning', 'Flava: A foundational language and vision alignment model']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_3', '5803800678022754468']}, {'title': 'Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning for Large Models: A Comprehensive Survey', 'abstract': ' Abstract Large models represent a groundbreaking advancement in multiple application fields, enabling remarkable achievements across various tasks. However, their unprecedented scale comes with significant computational costs. These models, often consisting of billions of parameters, require vast amounts of computational resources for execution. Especially, the expansive scale and computational demands pose considerable challenges when customizing them for particular downstream tasks, particularly over the hardware platforms constrained by computational capabilities. Parameter Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) provides a practical solution by efficiently adapt the large models over the various downstream tasks. In particular, PEFT refers to the process of adjusting the parameters of a pre-trained large models to adapt it to a specific task or domain while minimizing the number of additional parameters introduced or computational resources required. This approach is particularly important when dealing with large-scale language models with high parameter counts, as fine-tuning these models from scratch can be computationally expensive and resource-intensive, posing considerable challenges in the supporting system platform design. In this survey, we present comprehensive studies of various PEFT algorithms, examining their performance and computational overhead. Moreover, we provide an overview of applications developed using different PEFT algorithms and discuss common techniques employed to mitigate computation costs for PEFT. In addition to the algorithmic perspective, we overview various real-world system designs to investigate the implementation costs associated with different PEFT algorithms. This survey serves as an indispensable resource for researchers aiming to understand both the PEFT algorithm and its system implementation, offering detailed insights into recent advancements and practical applications. ', 'sections': {'I Introduction': ['Summit: Iterative text summarization via chatgpt', 'Multilingual machine translation with large language models: Empirical results and analysis', 'Gentopia: A collaborative platform for tool-augmented llms', 'Language models are few-shot learners'], 'II Background II-A Computation flow for LLaMA': ['Root mean square layer normalization', 'Roformer: Enhanced transformer with rotary position embedding'], 'II Background II-C Downstream Tasks for LLM Evaluation': ['Can a suit of armor conduct electricity? a new dataset for open book question answering', 'The something something video database for learning and evaluating visual common sense', 'Hellaswag: Can a machine really finish your sentence?', 'Hmdb: a large video database for human motion recognition', 'Glue: A multi-task benchmark and analysis platform for natural language understanding', 'The pascal visual object classes (voc) challenge', 'Think you have solved question answering? try arc, the ai2 reasoning challenge', 'Boolq: Exploring the surprising difficulty of natural yes/no questions', 'Winogrande: An adversarial winograd schema challenge at scale', 'Microsoft coco: Common objects in context', 'Scene parsing through ade20k dataset', 'Socialiqa: Commonsense reasoning about social interactions', 'The kinetics human action video dataset', 'Piqa: Reasoning about physical commonsense in natural language'], 'III PEFT Taxonomy III-A Additive PEFT': ['The power of scale for parameter-efficient prompt tuning', 'Infoprompt: Information-theoretic soft prompt tuning for natural language understanding', 'Towards adaptive prefix tuning for parameter-efficient language model fine-tuning', 'Few-shot parameter-efficient fine-tuning is better and cheaper than in-context learning', 'Adamix: Mixture-of-adapter for parameter-efficient tuning of large language models', 'Prefix-tuning: Optimizing continuous prompts for generation', 'Spt: Learning to selectively insert prompts for better prompt tuning', 'Mera: Merging pretrained adapters for few-shot learning', 'P-tuning v2: Prompt tuning can be comparable to fine-tuning universally across scales and tasks', 'Adaptersoup: Weight averaging to improve generalization of pretrained language models', 'Smop: Towards efficient and effective prompt tuning with sparse mixture-of-prompts', 'Parameter-efficient multi-task fine-tuning for transformers via shared hypernetworks', 'Xprompt: Exploring the extreme of prompt tuning', 'Exploring universal intrinsic task subspace via prompt tuning', 'Adapterfusion: Non-destructive task composition for transfer learning', 'Parameter-efficient transfer learning for nlp', 'Codeprompt: Task-agnostic prefix tuning for program and language generation', 'Inference-time policy adapters (ipa): Tailoring extreme-scale lms without fine-tuning', 'On transferability of prompt tuning for natural language processing', 'Gpt understands, too', 'Late prompt tuning: A late prompt could be better than many prompts', 'Spot: Better frozen model adaptation through soft prompt transfer', 'Counter-interference adapter for multilingual machine translation', 'Krona: Parameter efficient tuning with kronecker adapter', 'Idpg: An instance-dependent prompt generation method', 'Prefix propagation: Parameter-efficient tuning for long sequences', 'Dept: Decomposed prompt tuning for parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Towards a unified view of parameter-efficient transfer learning', 'Ptp: Boosting stability and performance of prompt tuning with perturbation-based regularizer', 'Conditional adapters: Parameter-efficient transfer learning with fast inference', 'Universality and limitations of prompt tuning', 'When do prompting and prefix-tuning work? a theory of capabilities and limitations', 'Aprompt: Attention prompt tuning for efficient adaptation of pre-trained language models', 'Prototype-based hyperadapter for sample-efficient multi-task tuning', 'Scaling & shifting your features: A new baseline for efficient model tuning'], 'III PEFT Taxonomy III-B Selective PEFT': ['Sensitivity-aware visual parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Training neural networks with fixed sparse masks', 'The lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding sparse, trainable neural networks', 'Parameter-efficient fine-tuning without introducing new latency', 'On the effectiveness of parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Parameter-efficient transfer learning with diff pruning', 'Unified low-resource sequence labeling by sample-aware dynamic sparse finetuning', 'Neural architecture search for parameter-efficient fine-tuning of large pre-trained language models', 'Efficient fine-tuning of bert models on the edge', 'Bitfit: Simple parameter-efficient fine-tuning for transformer-based masked language-models', 'Cross-attention is all you need: Adapting pretrained transformers for machine translation', 'Composable sparse fine-tuning for cross-lingual transfer', 'Raise a child in large language model: Towards effective and generalizable fine-tuning'], 'III PEFT Taxonomy III-C Reparameterized PEFT': ['Lora+: Efficient low rank adaptation of large models', 'Dylora: Parameter efficient tuning of pre-trained models using dynamic search-free low-rank adaptation', 'A practical bayesian framework for backpropagation networks', 'Parameter-efficient model adaptation for vision transformers', 'Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Parameter-efficient fine-tuning without introducing new latency', 'Sparse low-rank adaptation of pre-trained language models', 'Dora: Weight-decomposed low-rank adaptation', 'Moelora: An moe-based parameter efficient fine-tuning method for multi-task medical applications', 'Versatile black-box optimization', 'Compacter: Efficient low-rank hypercomplex adapter layers', 'Intrinsic dimensionality explains the effectiveness of language model fine-tuning', 'Bayesian low-rank adaptation for large language models', 'A fast iterative shrinkage-thresholding algorithm for linear inverse problems', 'Lorahub: Efficient cross-task generalization via dynamic lora composition', 'Krona: Parameter efficient tuning with kronecker adapter', 'Adaptive budget allocation for parameter-efficient fine-tuning'], 'III PEFT Taxonomy III-D Hybrid PEFT': ['Llm-adapters: An adapter family for parameter-efficient fine-tuning of large language models', 'A tutorial on bayesian optimization', 'Parameter-efficient fine-tuning design spaces', 'Autoformer: Searching transformers for visual recognition', 'Neural prompt search', 'Towards a unified view of parameter-efficient transfer learning', 'Autopeft: Automatic configuration search for parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Unipelt: A unified framework for parameter-efficient language model tuning'], 'IV Efficient PEFT design IV-A KV-cache Management for PEFT Efficiency': ['Flexgen: High-throughput generative inference of large language models with a single gpu', 'Efficient memory management for large language model serving with pagedattention'], 'IV Efficient PEFT design IV-B Pruning Strategies for PEFT': ['One network, many masks: Towards more parameter-efficient transfer learning', 'Adapterdrop: On the efficiency of adapters in transformers', 'Pruning meets low-rank parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Adapterfusion: Non-destructive task composition for transfer learning', 'Structured pruning adapters', 'SparseAdapter: An easy approach for improving the parameter-efficiency of adapters'], 'IV Efficient PEFT design IV-C Quantization Strategies for PEFT': ['Qa-lora: Quantization-aware low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Make your pre-trained model reversible: From parameter to memory efficient fine-tuning', 'Godec: Randomized low-rank & sparse matrix decomposition in noisy case', 'Lq-lora: Low-rank plus quantized matrix decomposition for efficient language model finetuning', 'Memory-efficient fine-tuning of compressed large language models via sub-4-bit integer quantization', 'Loftq: Lora-fine-tuning-aware quantization for large language models', 'Qlora: Efficient finetuning of quantized llms', 'Revisiting the parameter efficiency of adapters from the perspective of precision redundancy', 'Bitdelta: Your fine-tune may only be worth one bit'], 'IV Efficient PEFT design IV-D Memory-efficient PEFT Methods': ['The reversible residual network: Backpropagation without storing activations', 'Parameter-efficient tuning for large language model without calculating its gradients', 'Make your pre-trained model reversible: From parameter to memory efficient fine-tuning', 'Res-tuning: A flexible and efficient tuning paradigm via unbinding tuner from backbone', 'Hypertuning: Toward adapting large language models without back-propagation', 'Lora-fa: Memory-efficient low-rank adaptation for large language models fine-tuning', 'Fine-tuning language models with just forward passes', 'Lst: Ladder side-tuning for parameter and memory efficient transfer learning', 'Side-tuning: a baseline for network adaptation via additive side networks'], 'V PEFT for DNNs of Other Applications V-A PEFT for LLMs – Beyond the Basics': ['Gear: An efficient kv cache compression recipe for near-lossless generative inference of llm', 'Llama-adapter v2: Parameter-efficient visual instruction model', 'Overcoming catastrophic forgetting in neural networks', 'Infusing hierarchical guidance into prompt tuning: A parameter-efficient framework for multi-level implicit discourse relation recognition', 'H2o: Heavy-hitter oracle for efficient generative inference of large language models', 'Roformer: Enhanced transformer with rotary position embedding', 'A survey of web information extraction systems', 'Vl-pet: Vision-and-language parameter-efficient tuning via granularity control', 'Continual learning in task-oriented dialogue systems', 'Prompt tuning pushes farther, contrastive learning pulls closer: A two-stage approach to mitigate social biases', 'Parameter-efficient multi-task fine-tuning for transformers via shared hypernetworks', 'Llama-adapter: Efficient fine-tuning of language models with zero-init attention', 'End-to-end open-domain question answering with bertserini', 'Mvp-tuning: Multi-view knowledge retrieval with prompt tuning for commonsense reasoning', 'Longqlora: Efficient and effective method to extend context length of large language models', 'Parameter-efficient transfer learning for nlp', 'Minigpt-4: Enhancing vision-language understanding with advanced large language models', 'Loftq: Lora-fine-tuning-aware quantization for large language models', 'Extending context window of large language models via positional interpolation', 'Controlling the extraction of memorized data from large language models via prompt-tuning', 'Toward continual learning for conversational agents', 'Flexgen: High-throughput generative inference of large language models with a single gpu', 'Continual prompt tuning for dialog state tracking', 'Unifying vision-and-language tasks via text generation', 'Tuning layernorm in attention: Towards efficient multi-modal llm finetuning', 'Federated learning of large language models with parameter-efficient prompt tuning and adaptive optimization', 'Self-critical sequence training for image captioning', 'Compacter: Efficient low-rank hypercomplex adapter layers', 'Fvqa: Fact-based visual question answering', 'On prefix-tuning for lightweight out-of-distribution detection', 'Make your pre-trained model reversible: From parameter to memory efficient fine-tuning', 'Orthogonal subspace learning for language model continual learning', 'Longlora: Efficient fine-tuning of long-context large language models', 'Visual instruction tuning', 'Vl-adapter: Parameter-efficient transfer learning for vision-and-language tasks'], 'V PEFT for DNNs of Other Applications V-B PEFT for ViTs': ['Learning to prompt for continual learning', 'Improving visual prompt tuning for self-supervised vision transformers', 'Scaling vision transformers to 22 billion parameters', 'Adaptformer: Adapting vision transformers for scalable visual recognition', 'Visual prompt tuning', 'Aim: Adapting image models for efficient video action recognition', 'An image is worth 16x16 words: Transformers for image recognition at scale.', 'St-adapter: Parameter-efficient image-to-video transfer learning', 'An empirical study of training self-supervised vision transformers', 'Vision transformer adapter for dense predictions', 'Learning semantic proxies from visual prompts for parameter-efficient fine-tuning in deep metric learning'], 'V PEFT for DNNs of Other Applications V-C PEFT for VLAs': ['Clip-adapter: Better vision-language models with feature adapters', 'Overcoming catastrophic forgetting in neural networks', 'Side adapter network for open-vocabulary semantic segmentation', 'Conditional prompt learning for vision-language models', 'Learning to prompt for vision-language models', 'A simple cache model for image recognition', 'Pointclip: Point cloud understanding by clip', 'Scaling up visual and vision-language representation learning with noisy text supervision', 'Diverse data augmentation with diffusions for effective test-time prompt tuning', 'Flava: A foundational language and vision alignment model', 'Prompt-aligned gradient for prompt tuning', 'Test-time prompt tuning for zero-shot generalization in vision-language models', 'Learning transferable visual models from natural language supervision', 'Supervision exists everywhere: A data efficient contrastive language-image pre-training paradigm', 'Maple: Multi-modal prompt learning', 'Tip-adapter: Training-free clip-adapter for better vision-language modeling', 'Prompting visual-language models for efficient video understanding', 'Zero-shot referring expression comprehension via structural similarity between images and captions', 'Zero-shot temporal action detection via vision-language prompting'], 'V PEFT for DNNs of Other Applications V-D PEFT for Diffusion Models': ['Ipdreamer: Appearance-controllable 3d object generation with image prompts', 'Contrastive diffusion model with auxiliary guidance for coarse-to-fine pet reconstruction', 'Lcm-lora: A universal stable-diffusion acceleration module', 'Multi-concept customization of text-to-image diffusion', 'Flamingo: a visual language model for few-shot learning', 'Adding conditional control to text-to-image diffusion models', 'Ip-adapter: Text compatible image prompt adapter for text-to-image diffusion models', 'Tune-a-video: One-shot tuning of image diffusion models for text-to-video generation', 'High-resolution image synthesis with latent diffusion models', 'Denoising diffusion probabilistic models', 'Concept sliders: Lora adaptors for precise control in diffusion models', 'An image is worth one word: Personalizing text-to-image generation using textual inversion', 'T2i-adapter: Learning adapters to dig out more controllable ability for text-to-image diffusion models'], 'VI System Design Challenge for PEFT VI-A System design for PEFT': ['Gpt-4'], 'VI System Design Challenge for PEFT VI-B Case study: Offsite-Tuning': ['Offsite-tuning: Transfer learning without full model'], 'VI System Design Challenge for PEFT VI-C Case Study: PetS': ['Z.\xa0Zhou, X.\xa0Wei, J.\xa0Zhang, and G.\xa0Sun, “{{\\{PetS}}\\}: A unified framework for {{\\{Parameter-Efficient}}\\} transformers serving,”'], 'VI System Design Challenge for PEFT VI-D Parallel PEFT Training Frameworks': ['S-lora: Serving thousands of concurrent lora adapters', 'Punica: Multi-tenant lora serving'], 'VII Conclusion and Future Directions VII-A Simplify hyperparameter tuning': ['Dylora: Parameter efficient tuning of pre-trained models using dynamic search-free low-rank adaptation'], 'VII Conclusion and Future Directions VII-B Establish a unified benchmark': ['Adapters: A unified library for parameter-efficient and modular transfer learning', 'MMDetection: Open mmlab detection toolbox and benchmark', 'Peft: State-of-the-art parameter-efficient fine-tuning methods'], 'VII Conclusion and Future Directions VII-E Serve more models and tasks': ['Video generation models as world simulators', 'Mamba: Linear-time sequence modeling with selective state spaces', 'Sequential modeling enables scalable learning for large vision models']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_3', '5037940536591680401']}]
searched_papers [{'title': 'Accelerating Deep Learning with Dynamic Data Pruning', 'abstract': ' Abstract Deep learning’s success has been attributed to the training of large, overparameterized models on massive amounts of data. As this trend continues, model training has become prohibitively costly, requiring access to powerful computing systems to train state-of-the-art networks. A large body of research has been devoted to addressing the cost per iteration of training through various model compression techniques like pruning and quantization. Less effort has been spent targeting the number of iterations. Previous work, such as forget scores and GraNd/EL2N scores, address this problem by identifying important samples within a full dataset and pruning the remaining samples, thereby reducing the iterations per epoch. Though these methods decrease the training time, they use expensive static scoring algorithms prior to training. When accounting for the scoring mechanism, the total run time is often increased. In this work, we address this shortcoming with dynamic data pruning algorithms. Surprisingly, we find that uniform random dynamic pruning can outperform the prior work at aggressive pruning rates. We attribute this to the existence of “sometimes” samples — points that are important to the learned decision boundary only some of the training time. To better exploit the subtlety of sometimes samples, we propose two algorithms, based on reinforcement learning techniques, to dynamically prune samples and achieve even higher accuracy than the random dynamic method. We test all our methods against a full-dataset baseline and the prior work on CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100, and we can reduce the training time by up to 2×\\times without significant performance loss. Our results suggest that data pruning should be understood as a dynamic process that is closely tied to a model’s training trajectory, instead of a static step based solely on the dataset alone. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['Curriculum learning', 'Learning Multiple Layers of Features from Tiny Images', 'Mixed Precision Training', 'Hudson, Ehsan Adeli, Russ Altman, Simran Arora, Sydney von Arx, Michael\xa0S', 'Estimating Example Difficulty Using Variance of Gradients', 'An Empirical Study of Example Forgetting During Deep Neural Network Learning'], '2 Related Work 2.1 Curriculum learning and active learning': ['Curriculum learning', 'Active Learning Literature Survey'], '2 Related Work 2.2 Static data pruning': ['An Empirical Study of Example Forgetting During Deep Neural Network Learning', 'Selection via Proxy: Efficient Data Selection for Deep Learning', 'Deep Learning on a Data Diet: Finding Important Examples Early in Training'], '3 Methods 3.2 Pruning selection criterion': ['Note on a Method for Calculating Corrected Sums of Squares and Products', 'Reinforcment Learning: An Introduction', 'Deep Learning on a Data Diet: Finding Important Examples Early in Training'], '4 Results and discussion': ['Automatic differentiation in PyTorch', 'Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition', 'Deep Learning on a Data Diet: Finding Important Examples Early in Training', 'Learning Multiple Layers of Features from Tiny Images']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_0', '3636478987576523311']}, {'title': 'Pruning Randomly Initialized Neural Networks with Iterative Randomization', 'abstract': ' Abstract Pruning the weights of randomly initialized neural networks plays an important role in the context of lottery ticket hypothesis. Ramanujan et al. [26] empirically showed that only pruning the weights can achieve remarkable performance instead of optimizing the weight values. However, to achieve the same level of performance as the weight optimization, the pruning approach requires more parameters in the networks before pruning and thus more memory space. To overcome this parameter inefficiency, we introduce a novel framework to prune randomly initialized neural networks with iteratively randomizing weight values (IteRand). Theoretically, we prove an approximation theorem in our framework, which indicates that the randomizing operations are provably effective to reduce the required number of the parameters. We also empirically demonstrate the parameter efficiency in multiple experiments on CIFAR-10 and ImageNet. The code is available at https://github.com/dchiji-ntt/iterand. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['The lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding sparse, trainable neural networks', 'Snip: Single-shot network pruning based on connection sensitivity', 'Optimal lottery tickets via subset sum: Logarithmic over-parameterization is sufficient', 'What’s hidden in a randomly weighted neural network?'], '2 Background Notation and setup.': ['Proving the lottery ticket hypothesis: Pruning is all you need', 'Optimal lottery tickets via subset sum: Logarithmic over-parameterization is sufficient', 'What’s hidden in a randomly weighted neural network?'], '4 Theoretical justification 4.1 Setup': ['Proving the lottery ticket hypothesis: Pruning is all you need', 'Optimal lottery tickets via subset sum: Logarithmic over-parameterization is sufficient'], '4 Theoretical justification 4.2 Formulation and main results': ['Optimal lottery tickets via subset sum: Logarithmic over-parameterization is sufficient'], '4 Theoretical justification 4.3 Proof ideas for Theorem 4.1': ['Proving the lottery ticket hypothesis: Pruning is all you need'], '5 Experiments': ['What’s hidden in a randomly weighted neural network?'], '5 Experiments Setup.': ['Learning multiple layers of features from tiny images', 'The lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding sparse, trainable neural networks', 'What’s hidden in a randomly weighted neural network?', 'ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge', 'Deep residual learning for image recognition'], '5 Experiments Parameter distributions.': ['torch.nn.init – PyTorch 1.8.1 documentation', 'Delving deep into rectifiers: Surpassing human-level performance on imagenet classification', 'What’s hidden in a randomly weighted neural network?'], '6 Related work Lottery ticket hypothesis': ['The lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding sparse, trainable neural networks', 'Optimal lottery tickets via subset sum: Logarithmic over-parameterization is sufficient', 'Deconstructing lottery tickets: Zeros, signs, and the supermask', 'Learning representations by back-propagating errors', 'Snip: Single-shot network pruning based on connection sensitivity', 'What’s hidden in a randomly weighted neural network?', 'Proving the lottery ticket hypothesis: Pruning is all you need', 'One ticket to win them all: generalizing lottery ticket initializations across datasets and optimizers'], '6 Related work Neural network pruning and regrowth': ['Scalable training of artificial neural networks with adaptive sparse connectivity inspired by network science', 'Deep rewiring: Training very sparse deep networks', 'Sparsity in deep learning: Pruning and growth for efficient inference and training in neural networks', 'Learning both weights and connections for efficient neural networks', 'Learning sparse neural networks through l_0 regularization', 'Dsd: Dense-sparse-dense training for deep neural networks', 'Comparing biases for minimal network construction with back-propagation', 'Variational dropout sparsifies deep neural networks'], '7 Limitations': ['Multi-prize lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding accurate binary neural networks by pruning a randomly weighted network', 'Optimal lottery tickets via subset sum: Logarithmic over-parameterization is sufficient', 'Deconstructing lottery tickets: Zeros, signs, and the supermask', 'Pruning from scratch', 'What’s hidden in a randomly weighted neural network?']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_1', '4034169521653446385']}, {'title': 'Robustness to Pruning Predicts Generalization in Deep Neural Networks', 'abstract': ' Abstract Existing generalization measures that aim to capture a model’s simplicity based on parameter counts or norms fail to explain generalization in overparameterized deep neural networks. In this paper, we introduce a new, theoretically motivated measure of a network’s simplicity which we call prunability: the smallest fraction of the network’s parameters that can be kept while pruning without adversely affecting its training loss. We show that this measure is highly predictive of a model’s generalization performance across a large set of convolutional networks trained on CIFAR-10, does not grow with network size unlike existing pruning-based measures, and exhibits high correlation with test set loss even in a particularly challenging double descent setting. Lastly, we show that the success of prunability cannot be explained by its relation to known complexity measures based on models’ margin, flatness of minima and optimization speed, finding that our new measure is similar to – but more predictive than – existing flatness-based measures, and that its predictions exhibit low mutual information with those of other baselines. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['Deep double descent: Where bigger models and more data hurt', 'Norm-based capacity control in neural networks', 'The state of sparsity in deep neural networks', 'Fantastic generalization measures and where to find them', 'Understanding deep learning requires rethinking generalization'], '2 Related Work': ['Non-vacuous generalization bounds at the imagenet scale: a pac-bayesian compression approach', 'Exploring generalization in deep learning', 'The lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding sparse, trainable neural networks', 'Stochastic complexity and modeling', 'Learning both weights and connections for efficient neural network', 'Fantastic generalization measures and where to find them', 'Norm-based capacity control in neural networks', 'On the importance of single directions for generalization', 'Dropout: a simple way to prevent neural networks from overfitting', 'On the uniform convergence of relative frequencies of events to their probabilities', 'Rethinking parameter counting in deep models: Effective dimensionality revisited', 'Identity mappings in deep residual networks', 'The state of sparsity in deep neural networks', 'Keeping neural networks simple by minimizing the description length of the weights', 'Improving generalization of neural networks through pruning', 'Predicting the generalization gap in deep networks with margin distributions'], '2 Related Work 2.1 Notation': ['Fantastic generalization measures and where to find them'], '3 Prunability': ['What is the state of neural network pruning?', 'Dropout: a simple way to prevent neural networks from overfitting', 'Pac-bayesian model averaging', 'A pac-bayesian tutorial with a dropout bound'], '3 Prunability 3.1 Definition': ['What is the state of neural network pruning?'], '4 Experimental Results and Analysis': ['Fantastic generalization measures and where to find them'], '4 Experimental Results and Analysis 4.1 Baselines': ['Fantastic generalization measures and where to find them', 'Revisiting the train loss: an efficient performance estimator for neural architecture search', 'Predicting the generalization gap in deep networks with margin distributions', 'Non-vacuous generalization bounds at the imagenet scale: a pac-bayesian compression approach'], '4 Experimental Results and Analysis 4.2 Models': ['Fantastic generalization measures and where to find them', 'Predicting the generalization gap in deep networks with margin distributions', 'Network in network'], '4 Experimental Results and Analysis 4.3 Evaluation Metrics': ['Fantastic generalization measures and where to find them', 'Equivalence and synthesis of causal models', 'Predicting the generalization gap in deep networks with margin distributions'], '4 Experimental Results and Analysis 4.4 Results': ['Fantastic generalization measures and where to find them', 'Rethinking parameter counting in deep models: Effective dimensionality revisited', 'Deep double descent: Where bigger models and more data hurt', 'Non-vacuous generalization bounds at the imagenet scale: a pac-bayesian compression approach'], '5 Conclusion': ['Computing nonvacuous generalization bounds for deep (stochastic) neural networks with many more parameters than training data', 'Deep double descent: Where bigger models and more data hurt', 'Rethinking parameter counting in deep models: Effective dimensionality revisited']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_2', '8233515426919881926']}, {'title': 'RGP: Neural Network Pruning through Its Regular Graph Structure', 'abstract': ' Abstract Lightweight model design has become an important direction in the application of deep learning technology, pruning is an effective mean to achieve a large reduction in model parameters and FLOPs. The existing neural network pruning methods mostly start from the importance of parameters, and design parameter evaluation metrics to perform parameter pruning iteratively. These methods are not studied from the perspective of model topology, may be effective but not efficient, and requires completely different pruning for different datasets. In this paper, we study the graph structure of the neural network, and propose regular graph based pruning (RGP) to perform a one-shot neural network pruning. We generate a regular graph, set the node degree value of the graph to meet the pruning ratio, and reduce the average shortest path length of the graph by swapping the edges to obtain the optimal edge distribution. Finally, the obtained graph is mapped into a neural network structure to realize pruning. Experiments show that the average shortest path length of the graph is negatively correlated with the classification accuracy of the corresponding neural network, and the proposed RGP shows a strong precision retention capability with extremely high parameter reduction (more than 90%) and FLOPs reduction (more than 90%). ', 'sections': {'1 Introductions': ['Do deep nets really need to be deep?', 'Graph structure of neural networks', 'Imagenet classification with deep convolutional neural networks', 'Going deeper with convolutions', 'Very deep convolutional networks for large-scale image recognition', 'The lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding sparse, trainable neural networks', 'Densely connected convolutional networks', 'Deep residual learning for image recognition'], '2 Related Work': ['A systematic dnn weight pruning framework using alternating direction method of multipliers', 'The lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding sparse, trainable neural networks', 'Dsd: regularizing deep neural networks with dense-sparse-dense training flow', 'Learning both weights and connections for efficient neural network', 'Pruning via iterative ranking of sensitivity statistics', 'Hydra: Pruning adversarially robust neural networks', 'SINGLE-SHOT NETWORK PRUNING BASED ON CONNECTION SENSITIVITY', 'Soft filter pruning for accelerating deep convolutional neural networks', 'Channel pruning via automatic structure search', 'Autopruner: An end-to-end trainable filter pruning method for efficient deep model inference', 'Dynamic sparse training: Find efficient sparse network from scratch with trainable masked layers', 'Pruning filter in filter', 'Proving the lottery ticket hypothesis: Pruning is all you need', 'Dynamic model pruning with feedback', 'To prune, or not to prune: exploring the efficacy of pruning for model compression'], '3 Regular Graph Based Pruning of Neural Network 3.1 Graph pruning to DNN pruning': ['Graph structure of neural networks'], '3 Regular Graph Based Pruning of Neural Network 3.2 Regular graph as the search space': ['Entangled networks, super-homogeneity and optimal network topology'], '4 Experiments and Results 4.1 DNN models and datasets': ['Learning multiple layers of features from tiny images', 'Very deep convolutional networks for large-scale image recognition', 'Automatic differentiation in pytorch', 'Reading digits in natural images with unsupervised feature learning', 'Deep residual learning for image recognition'], '4 Experiments and Results 4.4 Comparison with other neural network structure pruning methods': ['Trp: Trained rank pruning for efficient deep neural networks', 'Hrank: Filter pruning using high-rank feature map']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_1', '1163766272917944885']}, {'title': 'Efficient Processing of Deep Neural Networks: A Tutorial and Survey', 'abstract': ' Abstract Deep neural networks (DNNs) are currently widely used for many artificial intelligence (AI) applications including computer vision, speech recognition, and robotics. While DNNs deliver state-of-the-art accuracy on many AI tasks, it comes at the cost of high computational complexity. Accordingly, techniques that enable efficient processing of DNNs to improve energy efficiency and throughput without sacrificing application accuracy or increasing hardware cost are critical to the wide deployment of DNNs in AI systems. This article aims to provide a comprehensive tutorial and survey about the recent advances towards the goal of enabling efficient processing of DNNs. Specifically, it will provide an overview of DNNs, discuss various hardware platforms and architectures that support DNNs, and highlight key trends in reducing the computation cost of DNNs either solely via hardware design changes or via joint hardware design and DNN algorithm changes. It will also summarize various development resources that enable researchers and practitioners to quickly get started in this field, and highlight important benchmarking metrics and design considerations that should be used for evaluating the rapidly growing number of DNN hardware designs, optionally including algorithmic co-designs, being proposed in academia and industry. The reader will take away the following concepts from this article: understand the key design considerations for DNNs; be able to evaluate different DNN hardware implementations with benchmarks and comparison metrics; understand the trade-offs between various hardware architectures and platforms; be able to evaluate the utility of various DNN design techniques for efficient processing; and understand recent implementation trends and opportunities. ', 'sections': {'I Introduction': ['Deepdriving: Learning affordance for direct perception in autonomous driving', 'Mastering the game of Go with deep neural networks and tree search', 'Dermatologist-level classification of skin cancer with deep neural networks', 'Recent advances in deep learning for speech research at Microsoft', 'ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Deep learning'], 'II Background on Deep Neural Networks (DNN) II-A Artificial Intelligence and DNNs': ['A million spiking-neuron integrated circuit with a scalable communication network and interface', 'Convolutional networks for fast, energy-efficient neuromorphic computing'], 'II Background on Deep Neural Networks (DNN) II-C Inference versus Training': ['Fast training of convolutional networks through FFTs'], 'II Background on Deep Neural Networks (DNN) II-D Development History': ['Handwritten digit recognition: applications of neural network chips and automatic learning', 'Recent advances in deep learning for speech research at Microsoft', 'Adaptive switching circuits', 'ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition', 'ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge'], 'II Background on Deep Neural Networks (DNN) II-E Applications of DNN': ['Dermatologist-level classification of skin cancer with deep neural networks', 'Learning deep control policies for autonomous aerial vehicles with mpc-guided policy search', 'Safe, multi-agent, reinforcement learning for autonomous driving', 'Mastering the game of Go with deep neural networks and tree search', 'Natural language processing (almost) from scratch', 'Big, big, big data: higher and higher resolution video surveillance', 'The Next Wave of Deep Learning Applications', 'Complete Visual Networking Index (VNI) Forecast', 'Deep learning for identifying metastatic breast cancer', 'Wavenet: A generative model for raw audio', 'Neural networks improve brain cancer detection with raman spectroscopy in the presence of operating room light artifacts', 'Playing Atari with Deep Reinforcement Learning', 'Two-stream convolutional networks for action recognition in videos', 'Reinforcement learning: A survey', 'Recent advances in deep learning for speech research at Microsoft', 'Fully Convolutional Networks for Semantic Segmentation', 'From Perception to Decision: A Data-driven Approach to End-to-end Motion Planning for Autonomous Ground Robots', 'ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge', 'End-to-end training of deep visuomotor policies', 'Deep neural networks for acoustic modeling in speech recognition: The shared views of four research groups', 'Cognitive mapping and planning for visual navigation', 'Rich Feature Hierarchies for Accurate Object Detection and Semantic Segmentation', 'The human splicing code reveals new insights into the genetic determinants of disease'], 'III Overview of DNNs': ['Long short-term memory'], 'III Overview of DNNs III-A Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs)': ['Mastering the game of Go with deep neural networks and tree search', 'Deep convolutional neural networks for LVCSR', 'Fast and Accurate Deep Network Learning by Exponential Linear Units (ELUs)', 'Improving deep neural network acoustic models using generalized maxout networks', 'End-to-end training of deep visuomotor policies', 'Rectifier nonlinearities improve neural network acoustic models', 'ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition', 'Batch normalization: Accelerating deep network training by reducing internal covariate shift', 'Delving deep into rectifiers: Surpassing human-level performance on imagenet classification', 'Rectified Linear Units Improve Restricted Boltzmann Machines'], 'III Overview of DNNs III-B Popular DNN Models': ['Handwritten digit recognition: applications of neural network chips and automatic learning', 'Inception-v4, Inception-ResNet and the Impact of Residual Connections on Learning', 'Going Deeper With Convolutions', 'OverFeat: Integrated Recognition, Localization and Detection using Convolutional Networks', 'Network in Network', 'ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition', 'Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition', 'Batch normalization: Accelerating deep network training by reducing internal covariate shift', 'Do Deep Convolutional Nets Really Need to be Deep and Convolutional?', 'Gradient-based learning applied to document recognition', 'Rethinking the inception architecture for computer vision', 'ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge'], 'IV DNN development resources IV-A Frameworks': ['Eyeriss: An Energy-Efficient Reconfigurable Accelerator for Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Caffe: Convolutional architecture for fast feature embedding', 'Deep Learning Frameworks'], 'IV DNN development resources IV-B Models': ['Caffe LeNet MNIST'], 'IV DNN development resources IV-C Popular Datasets for Classification': ['Fractional max-pooling', 'Going Deeper With Convolutions', 'ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition', 'Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition', 'Regularization of neural networks using dropconnect', 'The CIFAR-10 dataset', 'THE MNIST DATABASE of handwritten digits', '80 million tiny images: A large data set for nonparametric object and scene recognition', 'Gradient-based learning applied to document recognition', 'Convolutional deep belief networks on cifar-10', 'ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge'], 'IV DNN development resources IV-D Datasets for Other Tasks': ['Google Open Images', 'Microsoft Common Objects in Context (COCO) dataset', 'YouTube-8M', 'AudioSet', 'Pascal VOC data sets'], 'V Hardware for DNN Processing': ['Facebook unveils Big Basin, new server geared for deep learning'], 'V Hardware for DNN Processing V-A Accelerate Kernel Computation on CPU and GPU Platforms': ['Intel Math Kernel Library', 'Fast training of convolutional networks through FFTs', 'Minimizing computation in convolutional neural networks', 'Fast algorithms for convolutional neural networks'], 'V Hardware for DNN Processing V-B Energy-Efficient Dataflow for Accelerators': ['A 240 G-ops/s Mobile Coprocessor for Deep Neural Networks', 'Computing’s energy problem (and what we can do about it)', 'A Massively Parallel Coprocessor for Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Eyeriss: A Spatial Architecture for Energy-Efficient Dataflow for Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Deep Learning with Limited Numerical Precision', 'Memory-centric accelerator design for Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Optimizing FPGA-based Accelerator Design for Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC): Algorithms and Architectures', 'Fused-layer CNN accelerators', 'DianNao: A Small-footprint High-throughput Accelerator for Ubiquitous Machine-learning', 'Eyeriss: An Energy-Efficient Reconfigurable Accelerator for Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Using Dataflow to Optimize Energy Efficiency of Deep Neural Network Accelerators', 'ShiDianNao: Shifting Vision Processing Closer to the Sensor', 'DaDianNao: A Machine-Learning Supercomputer'], 'VI Near-Data Processing VI-A DRAM': ['Neurocube: A programmable digital neuromorphic architecture with high-density 3D memory', 'TETRIS: Scalable and Efficient Neural Network Acceleration with 3D Memory', 'Hybrid memory cube new DRAM architecture increases density and performance', 'DaDianNao: A Machine-Learning Supercomputer', 'Embedded DRAM development: Technology, physical design, and application issues', 'High bandwidth memory (HBM) DRAM'], 'VI Near-Data Processing VI-B SRAM': ['Error-adaptive classifier boosting (EACB): Exploiting data-driven training for highly fault-tolerant hardware', 'A machine-learning classifier implemented in a standard 6T SRAM array'], 'VI Near-Data Processing VI-C Non-volatile Resistive Memories': ['Neuromorphic architectures with electronic synapses', 'PRIME: A Novel Processing-In-Memory Architecture for Neural Network Computation in ReRAM-based Main Memory', 'Tutorial on Emerging Memory Devices', 'International technology roadmap for semiconductors (ITRS)', 'ISAAC: A Convolutional Neural Network Accelerator with In-Situ Analog Arithmetic in Crossbars', 'Memristor-the missing circuit element', 'Training and operation of an integrated neuromorphic network based on metal-oxide memristors'], 'VI Near-Data Processing VI-D Sensors': ['A matrix-multiplying ADC implementing a machine-learning classifier directly with data conversion', 'A 2.5 GHz 7.7 TOPS/W switched-capacitor matrix multiplier with co-designed local memory in 40nm', 'ASP Vision: Optically Computing the First Layer of Convolutional Neural Networks using Angle Sensitive Pixels', 'RedEye: analog ConvNet image sensor architecture for continuous mobile vision', 'A 180nm CMOS image sensor with on-chip optoelectronic image compression'], 'VII Co-design of DNN models and Hardware VII-A Reduce Precision': ['Trained Ternary Quantization', 'A machine-learning classifier implemented in a standard 6T SRAM array', 'Hardware-oriented Approximation of Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Google Takes Unconventional Route with Homegrown Machine Learning Chips', 'Nvidia Pushes Deep Learning Inference With New Pascal GPUs', 'Ternary weight networks', 'Lognet: Energy-Efficient Neural Networks Using Logrithmic Computations', 'Computing’s energy problem (and what we can do about it)', 'XNOR-Net: ImageNet Classification Using Binary Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Stripes: Bit-serial deep neural network computing', 'Quantized neural networks: Training neural networks with low precision weights and activations', 'BRein Memory: A 13-Layer 4.2 K Neuron/0.8 M Synapse Binary/Ternary Reconfigurable In-Memory Deep Neural Network Accelerator in 65nm CMOS', 'Deep Learning with Limited Numerical Precision', 'Deep Compression: Compressing Deep Neural Networks with Pruning, Trained Quantization and Huffman Coding', 'Convolutional networks for fast, energy-efficient neuromorphic computing', 'DoReFa-Net: Training low bitwidth convolutional neural networks with low bitwidth gradients', 'Deep learning with low precision by half-wave gaussian quantization', 'A 0.3–2.6 TOPS/W precision-scalable processor for real-time large-scale ConvNets', 'Binarynet: Training deep neural networks with weights and activations constrained to+ 1 or-1', 'Binaryconnect: Training deep neural networks with binary weights during propagations', 'Incremental Network Quantization: Towards Lossless CNNs with Low-precision Weights', 'Compressing Neural Networks with the Hashing Trick', 'YodaNN: An Ultra-Low Power Convolutional Neural Network Accelerator Based on Binary Weights', 'Scalable and modularized RTL compilation of Convolutional Neural Networks onto FPGA'], 'VII Co-design of DNN models and Hardware VII-B Reduce Number of Operations and Model Size': ['SqueezeNet: AlexNet-level accuracy with 50x fewer parameters and <<1MB model size', 'DNN Energy Estimation', 'Compression of Deep Convolutional Neural Networks for Fast and Low Power Mobile Applications', 'Minerva: Enabling low-power, highly-accurate deep neural network accelerators', 'Rethinking the inception architecture for computer vision', 'Eyeriss: A Spatial Architecture for Energy-Efficient Dataflow for Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Speeding-Up Convolutional Neural Networks Using Fine-tuned CP-Decomposition', 'Exploiting Linear Structure Within Convolutional Networks for Efficient Evaluation', 'Exploring the regularity of sparse structure in convolutional neural networks', 'Xception: Deep Learning With Depthwise Separable Convolutions', 'Deep Compression: Compressing Deep Neural Networks with Pruning, Trained Quantization and Huffman Coding', 'Cnvlutin: ineffectual-neuron-free deep neural network computing', 'Learning both weights and connections for efficient neural networks', 'Designing Energy-Efficient Convolutional Neural Networks using Energy-Aware Pruning', 'EIE: efficient inference engine on compressed deep neural network', 'Mobilenets: Efficient convolutional neural networks for mobile vision applications', 'Model Compression', 'Learning structured sparsity in deep neural networks', 'Optimal Brain Damage', 'Two-dimensional signal and image processing', 'Network in Network', 'Scalpel: Customizing dnn pruning to the underlying hardware parallelism', 'A scalable sparse matrix-vector multiplication kernel for energy-efficient sparse-blas on FPGAs', 'Distilling the Knowledge in a Neural Network', 'Fitnets: Hints for Thin Deep Nets', 'Eyeriss: An Energy-Efficient Reconfigurable Accelerator for Deep Convolutional Neural Networks', 'Scnn: An accelerator for compressed-sparse convolutional neural networks'], 'VIII Benchmarking Metrics for DNN Evaluation and Comparison': ['Benchmarking DNN Processors'], 'VIII Benchmarking Metrics for DNN Evaluation and Comparison VIII-A Metrics for DNN Models': ['Designing Energy-Efficient Convolutional Neural Networks using Energy-Aware Pruning']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_1', '4188001807463143072']}]
searched_papers [{'title': 'Machine Learning for Synthetic Data Generation: A Review', 'abstract': ' Abstract Machine learning heavily relies on data, but real-world applications often encounter various data-related issues. These include data of poor quality, insufficient data points leading to under-fitting of machine learning models, and difficulties in data access due to concerns surrounding privacy, safety, and regulations. In light of these challenges, the concept of synthetic data generation emerges as a promising alternative that allows for data sharing and utilization in ways that real-world data cannot facilitate. This paper presents a comprehensive systematic review of existing studies that employ machine learning models for the purpose of generating synthetic data. The review encompasses various perspectives, starting with the applications of synthetic data generation, spanning computer vision, speech, natural language processing, healthcare, and business domains. Additionally, it explores different machine learning methods, with particular emphasis on neural network architectures and deep generative models. The paper also addresses the crucial aspects of privacy and fairness concerns related to synthetic data generation. Furthermore, this study identifies the challenges and opportunities prevalent in this emerging field, shedding light on the potential avenues for future research. By delving into the intricacies of synthetic data generation, this paper aims to contribute to the advancement of knowledge and inspire further exploration in synthetic data generation. ', 'sections': {'I Introduction': ['Artificial intelligence', 'Synthetic data', 'Comparative assessment and novel strategy on methods for imputing proteomics data', 'Synthetic data for deep learning', 'What artificial intelligence can and can’t do right now', 'Machine learning: Trends, perspectives, and prospects', 'Data scarcity, robustness and extreme multi-label classification', 'Learning from synthetic data for crowd counting in the wild', 'A review of feature selection methods on synthetic data', 'Data quality assessment', 'The real deal about synthetic data'], 'II Application': ['The real deal about synthetic data'], 'II Application II-A Vision': ['Synthetic data generation using dcgan for improved traffic sign recognition', 'Learning from synthetic data: Addressing domain shift for semantic segmentation', 'Fake it till you make it: face analysis in the wild using synthetic data alone', 'Mt-uda: Towards unsupervised cross-modality medical image segmentation with limited source labels', 'Learning semantic segmentation from synthetic data: A geometrically guided input-output adaptation approach', 'Towards a deeper understanding of adversarial losses'], 'II Application II-B Voice': ['Synthasr: Unlocking synthetic data for speech recognition', 'Feature sparsity analysis for i-vector based speaker verification', 'Exploring the application of synthetic audio in training keyword spotters', 'Tandem deep features for text-dependent speaker verification', 'Modeling spectral envelopes using restricted boltzmann machines and deep belief networks for statistical parametric speech synthesis'], 'II Application II-C Natural Language Processing (NLP)': ['Relgan: Relational generative adversarial networks for text generation', 'Synthetic data generation using dcgan for improved traffic sign recognition', 'An extensive empirical study of feature selection metrics for text classification', 'Using synthetic audio to improve the recognition of out-of-vocabulary words in end-to-end asr systems', 'Bleurt: Learning robust metrics for text generation', 'Synthetic text generation with differential privacy: A simple and practical recipe'], 'II Application II-D Healthcare': ['MolGAN: An implicit generative model for small molecular graphs', 'Molecular de-novo design through deep reinforcement learning', 'Security techniques for the electronic health records', 'Corgan: Correlation-capturing convolutional generative adversarial networks for generating synthetic healthcare records', 'Cot: an efficient and accurate method for detecting marker genes among many subtypes', 'The problem of fairness in synthetic healthcare data', 'Generating high-fidelity synthetic patient data for assessing machine learning healthcare software', 'MIMOSA: Multi-constraint molecule sampling for molecule optimization', 'Antibody Complementarity Determining Regions (CDRs) design using constrained energy model', 'Deep generative models for synthetic data', 'Generation and evaluation of synthetic patient data', 'Multi-omics data integration for identifying disease specific biological pathways', 'Automatic chemical design using a data-driven continuous representation of molecules', 'GeoDiff: A geometric diffusion model for molecular conformation generation', 'Synthetic data in machine learning for medicine and healthcare', 'Generating multi-label discrete patient records using generative adversarial networks', 'The art and practice of structure-based drug design: a molecular modeling perspective', 'Synsys: A synthetic data generation system for healthcare applications', 'A graph-based genetic algorithm and generative model/monte carlo tree search for the exploration of chemical space'], 'II Application II-E Business': ['Is this real? generating synthetic data that looks real', 'Empirical evaluation on synthetic data generation with generative adversarial network', 'On the utility of synthetic data: An empirical evaluation on machine learning tasks', 'Practical synthetic data generation: balancing privacy and the broad availability of data', 'Generating synthetic data in finance: opportunities, challenges and pitfalls', 'The real deal about synthetic data'], 'II Application II-F Education': ['The role of a reference synthetic data generator within the field of learning analytics.', 'Synthetic data for social good', 'Protecting student privacy with synthetic data from generative adversarial networks'], 'II Application II-G Location and Trajectory Generation': ['Differentially private sequential data publication via variable-length n-grams', 'Location privacy-preserving mechanisms in location-based services: A comprehensive survey', 'Privtrace: Differentially private trajectory synthesis by adaptive markov model', 'The algorithmic foundations of differential privacy', 'Utility-aware synthesis of differentially private and attack-resilient location traces', 'Synthesizing plausible privacy-preserving location traces', 'A dummy-based anonymization method based on user trajectory with pauses', 'Dpt: differentially private trajectory synthesis using hierarchical reference systems'], 'II Application II-H AI-Generated Content (AIGC)': ['Democratizing financial knowledge with chatgpt by openai: Unleashing the power of technology', 'Boundary crossing: an experimental study of individual perceptions toward aigc', 'Openai chatgpt generated results: Similarity index of artificial intelligence-based contents', 'A comprehensive survey of ai-generated content (aigc): A history of generative ai from gan to chatgpt'], 'III Deep Neural Network': ['Mixing real and synthetic data to enhance neural network training–a review of current approaches'], 'III Deep Neural Network III-A Multiple Layer Perception (MLP)': ['Deep Learning'], 'III Deep Neural Network III-B Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)': ['Deep Learning'], 'III Deep Neural Network III-C Recurrent Neural Network (RNN)': ['Bidirectional recurrent neural networks', 'Lstm can solve hard long time lag problems', 'Learning phrase representations using RNN Encoder–Decoder for statistical machine translation'], 'III Deep Neural Network III-D Graph Neural Network (GNN)': ['Adapting meta knowledge with heterogeneous information network for covid-19 themed malicious repository detection', 'Semi-supervised classification with graph convolutional networks'], 'III Deep Neural Network III-E Transformer': ['Language models are few-shot learners'], 'IV Generative AI IV-A Language Model': ['Natural language generation for electronic health records', 'Affect-LM: A neural language model for customizable affective text generation'], 'IV Generative AI IV-B Self-Supervised Learning (SSL)': ['Strategies for pre-training graph neural networks'], 'IV Generative AI IV-C Variational Autoencoder (VAE)': ['Auto-encoding variational bayes', 'Nvae: A deep hierarchical variational autoencoder', 'Automatic chemical design using a data-driven continuous representation of molecules', 'Understanding disentangling in β𝛽\x08eta-vae'], 'IV Generative AI IV-D Generative Adversarial Network (GAN)': ['Generative adversarial nets', 'Wasserstein generative adversarial networks'], 'IV Generative AI IV-E Reinforcement Learning (RL)': ['Adapting distilled knowledge for few-shot relation reasoning over knowledge graphs', 'Reinforcement learning: An introduction'], 'IV Generative AI IV-F Diffusion Model': ['Wavegrad: Estimating gradients for waveform generation', 'Deep unsupervised learning using nonequilibrium thermodynamics', 'Score-based generative modeling through stochastic differential equations', 'Graphebm: Molecular graph generation with energy-based models', 'Denoising diffusion probabilistic models'], 'V Privacy Risks and Prevention V-A Privacy Risks in Data Synthesis': ['Exploiting unintended feature leakage in collaborative learning', 'Deep leakage from gradients', 'Membership inference attacks against machine learning models', 'Logan: Membership inference attacks against generative models', 'Gan-leaks: A taxonomy of membership inference attacks against generative models'], 'V Privacy Risks and Prevention V-B Privacy Protection in Data Synthesis': ['Plausible deniability for privacy-preserving data synthesis', 'Local privacy and statistical minimax rates', 'Kamino: Constraint-aware differentially private data synthesis', 'PrivSyn: Differentially private data synthesis', 'Privbayes: Private data release via bayesian networks', 'Privacy-preserving generative deep neural networks support clinical data sharing', 'Ganobfuscator: Mitigating information leakage under gan via differential privacy', 'Federated generative privacy', 'Pate-gan: Generating synthetic data with differential privacy guarantees', 'Priview: practical differentially private release of marginal contingency tables', 'Compressive privacy generative adversarial network', 'Calm: Consistent adaptive local marginal for marginal release under local differential privacy', 'Compressive privacy: From information\\backslash/estimation theory to machine learning', 'Differentially private releasing via deep generative model (technical report)', 'Differentially private generative adversarial network', 'k-anonymity: A model for protecting privacy', 'Data synthesis via differentially private markov random fields', 'Privacy, accuracy, and consistency too: a holistic solution to contingency table release', 'Differentially private mixture of generative neural networks', 'Privacy-preserving synthetic data generation for recommendation systems', 'Synsys: A synthetic data generation system for healthcare applications', 'Privacy preserving synthetic data release using deep learning', 'Holoclean: Holistic data repairs with probabilistic inference'], 'V Privacy Risks and Prevention V-C Privacy Threats in Foundation Models': ['A non-parametric test to detect data-copying in generative models', 'Extracting training data from diffusion models', 'Deduplicating training data mitigates privacy risks in language models', 'Extracting training data from large language models.'], 'VI Fairness': ['A methodology for controlling bias and fairness in synthetic data generation', 'Fairgan: Fairness-aware generative adversarial networks', 'Can you fake it until you make it? impacts of differentially private synthetic data on downstream classification fairness', 'A survey on bias and fairness in machine learning', 'Generative adversarial networks for mitigating biases in machine learning systems', 'Trustworthy distributed ai systems: Robustness, privacy, and governance', 'Ethical and social risks of harm from language models', 'Differential privacy has disparate impact on model accuracy', 'Fairness gan: Generating datasets with fairness properties using a generative adversarial network', 'The problem of fairness in synthetic healthcare data'], 'VIII Evaluation Strategy': ['Real-valued (medical) time series generation with recurrent conditional gans', 'Enhance wound healing monitoring through a thermal imaging based smartphone app', 'Meta-hallucinator: Towards few-shot cross-modality cardiac image segmentation', 'Speech synthesis from neural decoding of spoken sentences'], 'IX Challenges and Opportunities': ['Synthetic data in machine learning for medicine and healthcare', 'Synthetic data for deep learning', 'The problem of fairness in synthetic healthcare data', 'Rank-based outlier detection']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_1', '6836892157544142881']}, {'title': 'CroSSL: Cross-modal Self-Supervised Learning for Time-series through Latent Masking', 'abstract': ' Abstract. Limited availability of labeled data for machine learning on multimodal time-series extensively hampers progress in the field. Self-supervised learning (SSL) is a promising approach to learning data representations without relying on labels. However, existing SSL methods require expensive computations of negative pairs and are typically designed for single modalities, which limits their versatility. We introduce CroSSL (Cross-modal SSL), which puts forward two novel concepts: masking intermediate embeddings produced by modality-specific encoders, and their aggregation into a global embedding through a cross-modal aggregator that can be fed to downstream classifiers. CroSSL allows for handling missing modalities and end-to-end cross-modal learning without requiring prior data preprocessing for handling missing inputs or negative-pair sampling for contrastive learning. We evaluate our method on a wide range of data, including motion sensors such as accelerometers or gyroscopes and biosignals (heart rate, electroencephalograms, electromyograms, electrooculograms, and electrodermal) to investigate the impact of masking ratios and masking strategies for various data types and the robustness of the learned representations to missing data. Overall, CroSSL outperforms previous SSL and supervised benchmarks using minimal labeled data, and also sheds light on how latent masking can improve cross-modal learning. Our code is open-sourced at https://github.com/dr-bell/CroSSL ', 'sections': {'1. Introduction': ['Masked reconstruction based self-supervision for human activity recognition', 'Selfhar: Improving human activity recognition through self-training with unlabeled data', 'Analysis of a sleep-dependent neuronal feedback loop: the slow-wave microcontinuity of the EEG', 'Multi-task self-supervised learning for human activity detection', 'COCOA: Cross Modality Contrastive Learning for Sensor Data', 'Remote healthcare for elderly people using wearables: a review', 'Deep multi-view learning methods: A review', 'Self-supervised Learning for Human Activity Recognition Using 700,000 Person-days of Wearable Data'], '2. Related Work': ['Representation learning with contrastive predictive coding', 'MultiMAE: Multi-modal Multi-task Masked Autoencoders', 'Multi-task self-supervised learning for human activity detection', 'COCOA: Cross Modality Contrastive Learning for Sensor Data', 'Multimodal deep learning for activity and context recognition', 'Masked autoencoders are scalable vision learners', 'Tera: Self-supervised learning of transformer encoder representation for speech', 'ColloSSL: Collaborative Self-Supervised Learning for Human Activity Recognition', 'Self-supervised Learning for Human Activity Recognition Using 700,000 Person-days of Wearable Data'], '3. Proposed Method: CroSSL 3.1. Problem Formulation': ['Barlow Twins: Self-Supervised Learning via Redundancy Reduction', 'Debiased Contrastive Learning', 'VICReg: Variance-Invariance-Covariance Regularization for Self-Supervised Learning', 'COCOA: Cross Modality Contrastive Learning for Sensor Data', 'Bootstrap Your Own Latent - A New Approach to Self-Supervised Learning', 'Time series change point detection with self-supervised contrastive predictive coding', 'Contrastive predictive coding for human activity recognition'], '3. Proposed Method: CroSSL 3.2. Theoretical Motivations': ['Contrastive multiview coding', 'On the Information Bottleneck Theory of Deep Learning'], '4. Evaluation 4.1. Datasets': ['Introducing WESAD, a Multimodal Dataset for Wearable Stress and Affect Detection', 'Introducing a new benchmarked dataset for activity monitoring', 'Analysis of a sleep-dependent neuronal feedback loop: the slow-wave microcontinuity of the EEG'], '4. Evaluation 4.2. Experiments Setup': ['COCOA: Cross Modality Contrastive Learning for Sensor Data', 'Contrastive multiview coding', 'Applying machine learning for sensor data analysis in interactive systems: Common pitfalls of pragmatic use and ways to avoid them'], '4. Evaluation 4.3. Baselines': ['Deep convolutional and lstm recurrent neural networks for multimodal wearable activity recognition', 'Contrastive multiview coding', 'Digging deeper: towards a better understanding of transfer learning for human activity recognition', 'Time series change point detection with self-supervised contrastive predictive coding', 'Data-efficient image recognition with contrastive predictive coding'], '5. Discussion and Limitations': ['Assessing the state of self-supervised human activity recognition using wearables', 'Self-supervised transfer learning of physiological representations from free-living wearable data']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_0', '5907229209982565750']}, {'title': 'Ego4D: Around the World in 3,000 Hours of Egocentric Video', 'abstract': ' Abstract We introduce Ego4D, a massive-scale egocentric video dataset and benchmark suite. It offers 3,670 hours of daily-life activity video spanning hundreds of scenarios (household, outdoor, workplace, leisure, etc.) captured by 931 unique camera wearers from 74 worldwide locations and 9 different countries. The approach to collection is designed to uphold rigorous privacy and ethics standards, with consenting participants and robust de-identification procedures where relevant. Ego4D dramatically expands the volume of diverse egocentric video footage publicly available to the research community. Portions of the video are accompanied by audio, 3D meshes of the environment, eye gaze, stereo, and/or synchronized videos from multiple egocentric cameras at the same event. Furthermore, we present a host of new benchmark challenges centered around understanding the first-person visual experience in the past (querying an episodic memory), present (analyzing hand-object manipulation, audio-visual conversation, and social interactions), and future (forecasting activities). By publicly sharing this massive annotated dataset and benchmark suite, we aim to push the frontier of first-person perception.  Project page: https://ego4d-data.org/ ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['ImageNet: A large-scale hierarchical image database', 'Detecting activities of daily living in first-person camera views'], '3 Ego4D Dataset': ['The kinetics human action video dataset'], '4 Narrations of Camera Wearer Activity': ['Scaling egocentric vision: The epic-kitchens dataset', 'HowTo100M: Learning a Text-Video Embedding by Watching Hundred Million Narrated Video Clips']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_3', '543362041606584751']}, {'title': 'Spatial and Semantic Consistency Regularizations for Pedestrian Attribute Recognition', 'abstract': ' Abstract While recent studies on pedestrian attribute recognition have shown remarkable progress in leveraging complicated networks and attention mechanisms, most of them neglect the inter-image relations and an important prior: spatial consistency and semantic consistency of attributes under surveillance scenarios. The spatial locations of the same attribute should be consistent between different pedestrian images, e.g., the “hat” attribute and the “boots” attribute are always located at the top and bottom of the picture respectively. In addition, the inherent semantic feature of the “hat” attribute should be consistent, whether it is a baseball cap, beret, or helmet. To fully exploit inter-image relations and aggregate human prior in the model learning process, we construct a Spatial and Semantic Consistency (SSC) framework that consists of two complementary regularizations to achieve spatial and semantic consistency for each attribute. Specifically, we first propose a spatial consistency regularization to focus on reliable and stable attribute-related regions. Based on the precise attribute locations, we further propose a semantic consistency regularization to extract intrinsic and discriminative semantic features. We conduct extensive experiments on popular benchmarks including PA100K, RAP, and PETA. Results show that the proposed method performs favorably against state-of-the-art methods without increasing parameters. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['Improve person re-identification with part awareness learning', 'Visual attention consistency under image transforms for multi-label image classification', 'Learning deep features for discriminative localization', 'Pedestrian attribute classification in surveillance: Database and evaluation', 'Pedestrian attribute recognition at far distance', 'Deeply learned attributes for crowded scene understanding', 'Pedestrian attribute recognition: A survey', 'Hydraplus-net: Attentive deep features for pedestrian analysis'], '2 Related Work': ['Improving pedestrian attribute recognition with weakly-supervised multi-scale attribute-specific localization', 'Long short-term memory', 'Visual attention consistency under image transforms for multi-label image classification', 'Multi-attribute learning for pedestrian attribute recognition in surveillance scenarios', 'Spatial transformer networks', 'Squeeze-and-excitation networks', 'Attribute recognition by joint recurrent learning of context and correlation', 'Edge boxes: Locating object proposals from edges', 'Pose guided deep model for pedestrian attribute recognition in surveillance scenarios', 'Deep imbalanced attribute classification using visual attention aggregation', 'Feature pyramid networks for object detection', 'Localization guided learning for pedestrian attribute recognition', 'Learning deep features for discriminative localization', 'Hierarchical feature embedding for attribute recognition', 'Weakly-supervised learning of mid-level features for pedestrian attribute recognition and localization', 'Hydraplus-net: Attentive deep features for pedestrian analysis'], '3 Methods 3.1 Baseline Method': ['A richly annotated pedestrian dataset for person retrieval in real surveillance scenarios', 'Multi-attribute learning for pedestrian attribute recognition in surveillance scenarios'], '3 Methods 3.2 Spatial Consistency Module': ['Learning deep features for discriminative localization', 'Deep residual learning for image recognition'], '3 Methods 3.4 Loss Function': ['Deep imbalanced attribute classification using visual attention aggregation'], '4 Experiments 4.1 Datasets and Evaluation Metrics': ['Rethinking of pedestrian attribute recognition: Realistic datasets with efficient method', 'A richly annotated pedestrian dataset for person retrieval in real surveillance scenarios', 'A richly annotated dataset for pedestrian attribute recognition', 'Pedestrian attribute recognition at far distance', 'Hydraplus-net: Attentive deep features for pedestrian analysis'], '4 Experiments 4.2 Implementation Details': ['Deep residual learning for image recognition'], '4 Experiments 4.3 Comparison to the State of the Arts': ['Visual attention consistency under image transforms for multi-label image classification', 'Improving pedestrian attribute recognition with weakly-supervised multi-scale attribute-specific localization', 'Deep imbalanced attribute classification using visual attention aggregation']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_2', '1418151334062801511']}, {'title': 'R2L: Distilling Neural Radiance Field to Neural Light Field for Efficient Novel View Synthesis', 'abstract': ' Abstract Recent research explosion on Neural Radiance Field (NeRF) shows the encouraging potential to represent complex scenes with neural networks. One major drawback of NeRF is its prohibitive inference time: Rendering a single pixel requires querying the NeRF network hundreds of times. To resolve it, existing efforts mainly attempt to reduce the number of required sampled points. However, the problem of iterative sampling still exists. On the other hand, Neural Light Field (NeLF) presents a more straightforward representation over NeRF in novel view synthesis – the rendering of a pixel amounts to one single forward pass without ray-marching. In this work, we present a deep residual MLP network (88 layers) to effectively learn the light field. We show the key to successfully learning such a deep NeLF network is to have sufficient data, for which we transfer the knowledge from a pre-trained NeRF model via data distillation. Extensive experiments on both synthetic and real-world scenes show the merits of our method over other counterpart algorithms. On the synthetic scenes, we achieve 26∼35×26\\sim 35\\times FLOPs reduction (per camera ray) and 28∼31×28\\sim 31\\times runtime speedup, meanwhile delivering significantly better (1.4∼2.8similar-to1.42.81.4\\sim 2.8 dB average PSNR improvement) rendering quality than NeRF without any customized parallelism requirement. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['An introduction to computational learning theory', 'Mip-nerf: A multiscale representation for anti-aliasing neural radiance fields', 'Model compression', 'DONeRF: Towards Real-Time Rendering of Compact Neural Radiance Fields using Depth Oracle Networks', 'Derf: Decomposed radiance fields', 'Image quality assessment: from error visibility to structural similarity', 'Learning implicit fields for generative shape modeling', 'Autoint: Automatic integration for fast neural volume rendering', 'Nerf: Representing scenes as neural radiance fields for view synthesis'], '2 Related Work': ['Derf: Decomposed radiance fields', 'Light field networks: Neural scene representations with single-evaluation rendering', 'X-fields: Implicit neural view-, light-and time-image interpolation', 'Knowledge transfer via distillation of activation boundaries formed by hidden neurons', 'Do deep nets really need to be deep?', 'Fitnets: Hints for thin deep nets', 'Learning neural light fields with ray-space embedding networks', 'Contrastive representation distillation', 'Baking neural radiance fields for real-time view synthesis', 'Learning efficient object detection models with knowledge distillation', 'DONeRF: Towards Real-Time Rendering of Compact Neural Radiance Fields using Depth Oracle Networks', 'Autoint: Automatic integration for fast neural volume rendering', 'Learning deep representations with probabilistic knowledge transfer', 'Distilling the knowledge in a neural network', 'Knowledge distillation via instance relationship graph', 'Neulf: Efficient novel view synthesis with neural 4d light field', 'Neural sparse voxel fields', 'Model compression', 'Fastnerf: High-fidelity neural rendering at 200fps', 'Light field rendering', 'The lumigraph', 'Paying more attention to attention: Improving the performance of convolutional neural networks via attention transfer', 'Kilonerf: Speeding up neural radiance fields with thousands of tiny mlps', 'The plenoptic function and the elements of early vision', 'Pytorch: An imperative style, high-performance deep learning library', 'Light field neural rendering', 'Nerf: Representing scenes as neural radiance fields for view synthesis'], '3 Methodology 3.1 Background: Neural Radiance Field (NeRF)': ['Ray tracing volume densities', 'Nerf: Representing scenes as neural radiance fields for view synthesis'], '3 Methodology 3.2 R2L: Distilling NeRF to NeLF': ['Learning neural light fields with ray-space embedding networks', 'Derf: Decomposed radiance fields', 'Nerf: Representing scenes as neural radiance fields for view synthesis', 'Deep residual learning for image recognition'], '3 Methodology 3.4 Ray Representation and Point Sampling': ['Light field networks: Neural scene representations with single-evaluation rendering', 'Nerf: Representing scenes as neural radiance fields for view synthesis'], '3 Methodology 3.5 Training with Hard Examples': ['Beyond hard negative mining: Efficient detector learning via block-circulant decomposition'], '3 Methodology 3.6 Implementation Details': ['Attention is all you need', 'Nerf: Representing scenes as neural radiance fields for view synthesis'], '4 Experiments': ['Adam: A method for stochastic optimization', 'Kilonerf: Speeding up neural radiance fields with thousands of tiny mlps', 'Learning neural light fields with ray-space embedding networks', 'Neural sparse voxel fields', 'Baking neural radiance fields for real-time view synthesis', 'DONeRF: Towards Real-Time Rendering of Compact Neural Radiance Fields using Depth Oracle Networks', 'Pytorch: An imperative style, high-performance deep learning library', 'Nerf-pytorch', 'X-fields: Implicit neural view-, light-and time-image interpolation', 'Nex: Real-time view synthesis with neural basis expansion', 'Autoint: Automatic integration for fast neural volume rendering', 'Nerf: Representing scenes as neural radiance fields for view synthesis'], '4 Experiments 4.1 NeRF Synthetic and Real-World Dataset': ['Image quality assessment: from error visibility to structural similarity', 'The unreasonable effectiveness of deep features as a perceptual metric'], '4 Experiments 4.2 DONeRF Synthetic Dataset': ['Flip: A difference evaluator for alternating images', 'DONeRF: Towards Real-Time Rendering of Compact Neural Radiance Fields using Depth Oracle Networks'], '4 Experiments 4.3 Ablation Study': ['Dropout: a simple way to prevent neural networks from overfitting', 'Batch normalization: Accelerating deep network training by reducing internal covariate shift', 'Deep residual learning for image recognition']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_3', '8529404105748417372']}]
