searched_papers [{'title': 'Zero-shot Referring Expression Comprehension via Structural Similarity Between Images and Captions', 'abstract': ' Abstract Zero-shot referring expression comprehension aims at localizing bounding boxes in an image corresponding to provided textual prompts, which requires: (i) a fine-grained disentanglement of complex visual scene and textual context, and (ii) a capacity to understand relationships among disentangled entities. Unfortunately, existing large vision-language alignment (VLA) models, e.g., CLIP, struggle with both aspects so cannot be directly used for this task. To mitigate this gap, we leverage large foundation models to disentangle both images and texts into triplets in the format of (subject,predicate,object)subjectpredicateobject(\\texttt{subject},\\texttt{predicate},\\texttt{object}). After that, grounding is accomplished by calculating the structural similarity matrix between visual and textual triplets with a VLA model, and subsequently propagate it to an instance-level similarity matrix. Furthermore, to equip VLA models with the ability of relationship understanding, we design a triplet-matching objective to fine-tune the VLA models on a collection of curated dataset containing abundant entity relationships. Experiments demonstrate that our visual grounding performance increase of up to 19.5% over the SOTA zero-shot model on RefCOCO/+/g. On the more challenging Who’s Waldo dataset, our zero-shot approach achieves comparable accuracy to the fully supervised model. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['Referring relationships', 'Dense and aligned captions (dac) promote compositional reasoning in vl models', 'Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Vision-and-language navigation: A survey of tasks, methods, and future directions', 'Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Learning transferable visual models from natural language supervision', 'When and why vision-language models behave like bags-of-words, and what to do about it?', 'Comclip: Training-free compositional image and text matching', 'Hico: A benchmark for recognizing human-object interactions in images', 'Structure-clip: Enhance multi-modal language representations with structure knowledge', 'Visual genome: Connecting language and vision using crowdsourced dense image annotations', 'Aligning bag of regions for open-vocabulary object detection', 'Ok-vqa: A visual question answering benchmark requiring external knowledge', 'Flava: A foundational language and vision alignment model', 'Generation and comprehension of unambiguous object descriptions', 'Gentopia: A collaborative platform for tool-augmented llms', 'A comprehensive survey of deep learning for image captioning'], '2 Related Work': ['Objects365: A large-scale, high-quality dataset for object detection', 'Dense and aligned captions (dac) promote compositional reasoning in vl models', 'Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Higher-order coreference resolution with coarse-to-fine inference', 'Flickr30k entities: Collecting region-to-phrase correspondences for richer image-to-sentence models', 'Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Incorporating structured representations into pretrained vision & language models using scene graphs', 'Simple bert models for relation extraction and semantic role labeling', 'Microsoft coco: Common objects in context', 'Hico: A benchmark for recognizing human-object interactions in images', 'Glipv2: Unifying localization and vision-language understanding', 'Visual genome: Connecting language and vision using crowdsourced dense image annotations', 'Nested named entity recognition', 'Refining event extraction through cross-document inference', 'Position-aware attention and supervised data improve slot filling', 'Deep semantic role labeling: What works and what’s next', 'Generation and comprehension of unambiguous object descriptions', 'When and why vision-language models behave like bags-of-words, and what to do about it?'], '3 Proposed Approach 3.1 Constructing Triplets': ['Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension'], '3 Proposed Approach 3.2 Grounding Based on the Structural Similarity': ['Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Generation and comprehension of unambiguous object descriptions'], '3 Proposed Approach 3.3 Enhanced Relational Understanding': ['Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Hico: A benchmark for recognizing human-object interactions in images', 'Grounded situation recognition', 'Visual genome: Connecting language and vision using crowdsourced dense image annotations', 'Dense and aligned captions (dac) promote compositional reasoning in vl models'], '4 Experiments 4.1 Setup': ['Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Microsoft coco: Common objects in context', 'Modeling context in referring expressions', 'Generation and comprehension of unambiguous object descriptions'], '4 Experiments 4.2 Implementation Details': ['Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Teaching structured vision & language concepts to vision & language models', 'Grounded situation recognition', 'Mattnet: Modular attention network for referring expression comprehension', 'Peft: State-of-the-art parameter-efficient fine-tuning methods'], '4 Experiments 4.3 Main Results': ['Grad-cam: Visual explanations from deep networks via gradient-based localization', 'Reclip: A strong zero-shot baseline for referring expression comprehension', 'Cpt: Colorful prompt tuning for pre-trained vision-language models', 'Consnet: Learning consistency graph for zero-shot human-object interaction detection', 'Who’s waldo? linking people across text and images', 'Mattnet: Modular attention network for referring expression comprehension', 'Contrastive learning for weakly supervised phrase grounding', 'Uniter: Universal image-text representation learning', 'Flava: A foundational language and vision alignment model']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_3', '5803800678022754468']}, {'title': 'Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning for Large Models: A Comprehensive Survey', 'abstract': ' Abstract Large models represent a groundbreaking advancement in multiple application fields, enabling remarkable achievements across various tasks. However, their unprecedented scale comes with significant computational costs. These models, often consisting of billions of parameters, require vast amounts of computational resources for execution. Especially, the expansive scale and computational demands pose considerable challenges when customizing them for particular downstream tasks, particularly over the hardware platforms constrained by computational capabilities. Parameter Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) provides a practical solution by efficiently adapt the large models over the various downstream tasks. In particular, PEFT refers to the process of adjusting the parameters of a pre-trained large models to adapt it to a specific task or domain while minimizing the number of additional parameters introduced or computational resources required. This approach is particularly important when dealing with large-scale language models with high parameter counts, as fine-tuning these models from scratch can be computationally expensive and resource-intensive, posing considerable challenges in the supporting system platform design. In this survey, we present comprehensive studies of various PEFT algorithms, examining their performance and computational overhead. Moreover, we provide an overview of applications developed using different PEFT algorithms and discuss common techniques employed to mitigate computation costs for PEFT. In addition to the algorithmic perspective, we overview various real-world system designs to investigate the implementation costs associated with different PEFT algorithms. This survey serves as an indispensable resource for researchers aiming to understand both the PEFT algorithm and its system implementation, offering detailed insights into recent advancements and practical applications. ', 'sections': {'I Introduction': ['Summit: Iterative text summarization via chatgpt', 'Multilingual machine translation with large language models: Empirical results and analysis', 'Gentopia: A collaborative platform for tool-augmented llms', 'Language models are few-shot learners'], 'II Background II-A Computation flow for LLaMA': ['Root mean square layer normalization', 'Roformer: Enhanced transformer with rotary position embedding'], 'II Background II-C Downstream Tasks for LLM Evaluation': ['Can a suit of armor conduct electricity? a new dataset for open book question answering', 'The something something video database for learning and evaluating visual common sense', 'Hellaswag: Can a machine really finish your sentence?', 'Hmdb: a large video database for human motion recognition', 'Glue: A multi-task benchmark and analysis platform for natural language understanding', 'The pascal visual object classes (voc) challenge', 'Think you have solved question answering? try arc, the ai2 reasoning challenge', 'Boolq: Exploring the surprising difficulty of natural yes/no questions', 'Winogrande: An adversarial winograd schema challenge at scale', 'Microsoft coco: Common objects in context', 'Scene parsing through ade20k dataset', 'Socialiqa: Commonsense reasoning about social interactions', 'The kinetics human action video dataset', 'Piqa: Reasoning about physical commonsense in natural language'], 'III PEFT Taxonomy III-A Additive PEFT': ['The power of scale for parameter-efficient prompt tuning', 'Infoprompt: Information-theoretic soft prompt tuning for natural language understanding', 'Towards adaptive prefix tuning for parameter-efficient language model fine-tuning', 'Few-shot parameter-efficient fine-tuning is better and cheaper than in-context learning', 'Adamix: Mixture-of-adapter for parameter-efficient tuning of large language models', 'Prefix-tuning: Optimizing continuous prompts for generation', 'Spt: Learning to selectively insert prompts for better prompt tuning', 'Mera: Merging pretrained adapters for few-shot learning', 'P-tuning v2: Prompt tuning can be comparable to fine-tuning universally across scales and tasks', 'Adaptersoup: Weight averaging to improve generalization of pretrained language models', 'Smop: Towards efficient and effective prompt tuning with sparse mixture-of-prompts', 'Parameter-efficient multi-task fine-tuning for transformers via shared hypernetworks', 'Xprompt: Exploring the extreme of prompt tuning', 'Exploring universal intrinsic task subspace via prompt tuning', 'Adapterfusion: Non-destructive task composition for transfer learning', 'Parameter-efficient transfer learning for nlp', 'Codeprompt: Task-agnostic prefix tuning for program and language generation', 'Inference-time policy adapters (ipa): Tailoring extreme-scale lms without fine-tuning', 'On transferability of prompt tuning for natural language processing', 'Gpt understands, too', 'Late prompt tuning: A late prompt could be better than many prompts', 'Spot: Better frozen model adaptation through soft prompt transfer', 'Counter-interference adapter for multilingual machine translation', 'Krona: Parameter efficient tuning with kronecker adapter', 'Idpg: An instance-dependent prompt generation method', 'Prefix propagation: Parameter-efficient tuning for long sequences', 'Dept: Decomposed prompt tuning for parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Towards a unified view of parameter-efficient transfer learning', 'Ptp: Boosting stability and performance of prompt tuning with perturbation-based regularizer', 'Conditional adapters: Parameter-efficient transfer learning with fast inference', 'Universality and limitations of prompt tuning', 'When do prompting and prefix-tuning work? a theory of capabilities and limitations', 'Aprompt: Attention prompt tuning for efficient adaptation of pre-trained language models', 'Prototype-based hyperadapter for sample-efficient multi-task tuning', 'Scaling & shifting your features: A new baseline for efficient model tuning'], 'III PEFT Taxonomy III-B Selective PEFT': ['Sensitivity-aware visual parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Training neural networks with fixed sparse masks', 'The lottery ticket hypothesis: Finding sparse, trainable neural networks', 'Parameter-efficient fine-tuning without introducing new latency', 'On the effectiveness of parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Parameter-efficient transfer learning with diff pruning', 'Unified low-resource sequence labeling by sample-aware dynamic sparse finetuning', 'Neural architecture search for parameter-efficient fine-tuning of large pre-trained language models', 'Efficient fine-tuning of bert models on the edge', 'Bitfit: Simple parameter-efficient fine-tuning for transformer-based masked language-models', 'Cross-attention is all you need: Adapting pretrained transformers for machine translation', 'Composable sparse fine-tuning for cross-lingual transfer', 'Raise a child in large language model: Towards effective and generalizable fine-tuning'], 'III PEFT Taxonomy III-C Reparameterized PEFT': ['Lora+: Efficient low rank adaptation of large models', 'Dylora: Parameter efficient tuning of pre-trained models using dynamic search-free low-rank adaptation', 'A practical bayesian framework for backpropagation networks', 'Parameter-efficient model adaptation for vision transformers', 'Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Parameter-efficient fine-tuning without introducing new latency', 'Sparse low-rank adaptation of pre-trained language models', 'Dora: Weight-decomposed low-rank adaptation', 'Moelora: An moe-based parameter efficient fine-tuning method for multi-task medical applications', 'Versatile black-box optimization', 'Compacter: Efficient low-rank hypercomplex adapter layers', 'Intrinsic dimensionality explains the effectiveness of language model fine-tuning', 'Bayesian low-rank adaptation for large language models', 'A fast iterative shrinkage-thresholding algorithm for linear inverse problems', 'Lorahub: Efficient cross-task generalization via dynamic lora composition', 'Krona: Parameter efficient tuning with kronecker adapter', 'Adaptive budget allocation for parameter-efficient fine-tuning'], 'III PEFT Taxonomy III-D Hybrid PEFT': ['Llm-adapters: An adapter family for parameter-efficient fine-tuning of large language models', 'A tutorial on bayesian optimization', 'Parameter-efficient fine-tuning design spaces', 'Autoformer: Searching transformers for visual recognition', 'Neural prompt search', 'Towards a unified view of parameter-efficient transfer learning', 'Autopeft: Automatic configuration search for parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Unipelt: A unified framework for parameter-efficient language model tuning'], 'IV Efficient PEFT design IV-A KV-cache Management for PEFT Efficiency': ['Flexgen: High-throughput generative inference of large language models with a single gpu', 'Efficient memory management for large language model serving with pagedattention'], 'IV Efficient PEFT design IV-B Pruning Strategies for PEFT': ['One network, many masks: Towards more parameter-efficient transfer learning', 'Adapterdrop: On the efficiency of adapters in transformers', 'Pruning meets low-rank parameter-efficient fine-tuning', 'Adapterfusion: Non-destructive task composition for transfer learning', 'Structured pruning adapters', 'SparseAdapter: An easy approach for improving the parameter-efficiency of adapters'], 'IV Efficient PEFT design IV-C Quantization Strategies for PEFT': ['Qa-lora: Quantization-aware low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Make your pre-trained model reversible: From parameter to memory efficient fine-tuning', 'Godec: Randomized low-rank & sparse matrix decomposition in noisy case', 'Lq-lora: Low-rank plus quantized matrix decomposition for efficient language model finetuning', 'Memory-efficient fine-tuning of compressed large language models via sub-4-bit integer quantization', 'Loftq: Lora-fine-tuning-aware quantization for large language models', 'Qlora: Efficient finetuning of quantized llms', 'Revisiting the parameter efficiency of adapters from the perspective of precision redundancy', 'Bitdelta: Your fine-tune may only be worth one bit'], 'IV Efficient PEFT design IV-D Memory-efficient PEFT Methods': ['The reversible residual network: Backpropagation without storing activations', 'Parameter-efficient tuning for large language model without calculating its gradients', 'Make your pre-trained model reversible: From parameter to memory efficient fine-tuning', 'Res-tuning: A flexible and efficient tuning paradigm via unbinding tuner from backbone', 'Hypertuning: Toward adapting large language models without back-propagation', 'Lora-fa: Memory-efficient low-rank adaptation for large language models fine-tuning', 'Fine-tuning language models with just forward passes', 'Lst: Ladder side-tuning for parameter and memory efficient transfer learning', 'Side-tuning: a baseline for network adaptation via additive side networks'], 'V PEFT for DNNs of Other Applications V-A PEFT for LLMs – Beyond the Basics': ['Gear: An efficient kv cache compression recipe for near-lossless generative inference of llm', 'Llama-adapter v2: Parameter-efficient visual instruction model', 'Overcoming catastrophic forgetting in neural networks', 'Infusing hierarchical guidance into prompt tuning: A parameter-efficient framework for multi-level implicit discourse relation recognition', 'H2o: Heavy-hitter oracle for efficient generative inference of large language models', 'Roformer: Enhanced transformer with rotary position embedding', 'A survey of web information extraction systems', 'Vl-pet: Vision-and-language parameter-efficient tuning via granularity control', 'Continual learning in task-oriented dialogue systems', 'Prompt tuning pushes farther, contrastive learning pulls closer: A two-stage approach to mitigate social biases', 'Parameter-efficient multi-task fine-tuning for transformers via shared hypernetworks', 'Llama-adapter: Efficient fine-tuning of language models with zero-init attention', 'End-to-end open-domain question answering with bertserini', 'Mvp-tuning: Multi-view knowledge retrieval with prompt tuning for commonsense reasoning', 'Longqlora: Efficient and effective method to extend context length of large language models', 'Parameter-efficient transfer learning for nlp', 'Minigpt-4: Enhancing vision-language understanding with advanced large language models', 'Loftq: Lora-fine-tuning-aware quantization for large language models', 'Extending context window of large language models via positional interpolation', 'Controlling the extraction of memorized data from large language models via prompt-tuning', 'Toward continual learning for conversational agents', 'Flexgen: High-throughput generative inference of large language models with a single gpu', 'Continual prompt tuning for dialog state tracking', 'Unifying vision-and-language tasks via text generation', 'Tuning layernorm in attention: Towards efficient multi-modal llm finetuning', 'Federated learning of large language models with parameter-efficient prompt tuning and adaptive optimization', 'Self-critical sequence training for image captioning', 'Compacter: Efficient low-rank hypercomplex adapter layers', 'Fvqa: Fact-based visual question answering', 'On prefix-tuning for lightweight out-of-distribution detection', 'Make your pre-trained model reversible: From parameter to memory efficient fine-tuning', 'Orthogonal subspace learning for language model continual learning', 'Longlora: Efficient fine-tuning of long-context large language models', 'Visual instruction tuning', 'Vl-adapter: Parameter-efficient transfer learning for vision-and-language tasks'], 'V PEFT for DNNs of Other Applications V-B PEFT for ViTs': ['Learning to prompt for continual learning', 'Improving visual prompt tuning for self-supervised vision transformers', 'Scaling vision transformers to 22 billion parameters', 'Adaptformer: Adapting vision transformers for scalable visual recognition', 'Visual prompt tuning', 'Aim: Adapting image models for efficient video action recognition', 'An image is worth 16x16 words: Transformers for image recognition at scale.', 'St-adapter: Parameter-efficient image-to-video transfer learning', 'An empirical study of training self-supervised vision transformers', 'Vision transformer adapter for dense predictions', 'Learning semantic proxies from visual prompts for parameter-efficient fine-tuning in deep metric learning'], 'V PEFT for DNNs of Other Applications V-C PEFT for VLAs': ['Clip-adapter: Better vision-language models with feature adapters', 'Overcoming catastrophic forgetting in neural networks', 'Side adapter network for open-vocabulary semantic segmentation', 'Conditional prompt learning for vision-language models', 'Learning to prompt for vision-language models', 'A simple cache model for image recognition', 'Pointclip: Point cloud understanding by clip', 'Scaling up visual and vision-language representation learning with noisy text supervision', 'Diverse data augmentation with diffusions for effective test-time prompt tuning', 'Flava: A foundational language and vision alignment model', 'Prompt-aligned gradient for prompt tuning', 'Test-time prompt tuning for zero-shot generalization in vision-language models', 'Learning transferable visual models from natural language supervision', 'Supervision exists everywhere: A data efficient contrastive language-image pre-training paradigm', 'Maple: Multi-modal prompt learning', 'Tip-adapter: Training-free clip-adapter for better vision-language modeling', 'Prompting visual-language models for efficient video understanding', 'Zero-shot referring expression comprehension via structural similarity between images and captions', 'Zero-shot temporal action detection via vision-language prompting'], 'V PEFT for DNNs of Other Applications V-D PEFT for Diffusion Models': ['Ipdreamer: Appearance-controllable 3d object generation with image prompts', 'Contrastive diffusion model with auxiliary guidance for coarse-to-fine pet reconstruction', 'Lcm-lora: A universal stable-diffusion acceleration module', 'Multi-concept customization of text-to-image diffusion', 'Flamingo: a visual language model for few-shot learning', 'Adding conditional control to text-to-image diffusion models', 'Ip-adapter: Text compatible image prompt adapter for text-to-image diffusion models', 'Tune-a-video: One-shot tuning of image diffusion models for text-to-video generation', 'High-resolution image synthesis with latent diffusion models', 'Denoising diffusion probabilistic models', 'Concept sliders: Lora adaptors for precise control in diffusion models', 'An image is worth one word: Personalizing text-to-image generation using textual inversion', 'T2i-adapter: Learning adapters to dig out more controllable ability for text-to-image diffusion models'], 'VI System Design Challenge for PEFT VI-A System design for PEFT': ['Gpt-4'], 'VI System Design Challenge for PEFT VI-B Case study: Offsite-Tuning': ['Offsite-tuning: Transfer learning without full model'], 'VI System Design Challenge for PEFT VI-C Case Study: PetS': ['Z.\xa0Zhou, X.\xa0Wei, J.\xa0Zhang, and G.\xa0Sun, “{{\\{PetS}}\\}: A unified framework for {{\\{Parameter-Efficient}}\\} transformers serving,”'], 'VI System Design Challenge for PEFT VI-D Parallel PEFT Training Frameworks': ['S-lora: Serving thousands of concurrent lora adapters', 'Punica: Multi-tenant lora serving'], 'VII Conclusion and Future Directions VII-A Simplify hyperparameter tuning': ['Dylora: Parameter efficient tuning of pre-trained models using dynamic search-free low-rank adaptation'], 'VII Conclusion and Future Directions VII-B Establish a unified benchmark': ['Adapters: A unified library for parameter-efficient and modular transfer learning', 'MMDetection: Open mmlab detection toolbox and benchmark', 'Peft: State-of-the-art parameter-efficient fine-tuning methods'], 'VII Conclusion and Future Directions VII-E Serve more models and tasks': ['Video generation models as world simulators', 'Mamba: Linear-time sequence modeling with selective state spaces', 'Sequential modeling enables scalable learning for large vision models']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_3', '5037940536591680401']}]
searched_papers [{'title': 'The Unreasonable Ineffectiveness of the Deeper Layers', 'abstract': ' Abstract We empirically study a simple layer-pruning strategy for popular families of open-weight pretrained LLMs, finding minimal degradation of performance on different question-answering benchmarks until after a large fraction (up to half) of the layers are removed. To prune these models, we identify the optimal block of layers to prune by considering similarity across layers; then, to “heal” the damage, we perform a small amount of finetuning. In particular, we use parameter-efficient finetuning (PEFT) methods, specifically quantization and Low Rank Adapters (QLoRA), such that each of our experiments can be performed on a single A100 GPU. From a practical perspective, these results suggest that layer pruning methods can complement other PEFT strategies to further reduce computational resources of finetuning on the one hand, and can improve the memory and latency of inference on the other hand. From a scientific perspective, the robustness of these LLMs to the deletion of layers implies either that current pretraining methods are not properly leveraging the parameters in the deeper layers of the network or that the shallow layers play a critical role in storing knowledge. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['Introducing chatgpt', 'Optimal brain damage', 'Llama 2: Open foundation and fine-tuned chat models', 'Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Tensor programs vi: Feature learning in infinite-depth neural networks', 'Go smol or go home', 'Shortgpt: Layers in large language models are more redundant than you expect', 'Gpt-4 technical report', 'Eliciting latent predictions from transformers with the tuned lens', 'Scaling laws for neural language models', 'Interpreting GPT: The Logit Lens', 'Qlora: Efficient finetuning of quantized llms', 'Neural ordinary differential equations', 'Llm. int8 (): 8-bit matrix multiplication for transformers at scale', 'Language models are unsupervised multitask learners.'], '2 Literature Review 2.1 Pruning': ['Slicegpt: Compress large language models by deleting rows and columns', 'Analyzing multi-head self-attention: Specialized heads do the heavy lifting, the rest can be pruned', 'Bert: Pre-training of deep bidirectional transformers for language understanding', 'wav2vec 2.0: A framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations', 'Pruning filters for efficient convnets', 'Attention is all you need', 'Can chatgpt understand too? a comparative study on chatgpt and fine-tuned bert', 'Large language model distillation doesn’t need a teacher.', 'Learning both weights and connections for efficient neural network', 'On the effect of dropping layers of pre-trained transformer models', 'Reducing transformer depth on demand with structured dropout', 'Language models are unsupervised multitask learners.', 'Structured pruning learns compact and accurate models', 'The truth is in there: Improving reasoning in language models with layer-selective rank reduction', 'Optimal brain damage', 'Dynabert: Dynamic bert with adaptive width and depth', 'Comflp: Correlation measure based fast search on asr layer pruning', 'Auto-sizing neural networks: With applications to n-gram language models', 'How contextual are contextualized word representations? comparing the geometry of bert, elmo, and gpt-2 embeddings'], '2 Literature Review 2.2 Model distillation': ['Distilling the knowledge in a neural network', 'Tinystories: How small can language models be and still speak coherent english?', 'Specializing smaller language models towards multi-step reasoning', 'Want to reduce labeling cost? gpt-3 can help', 'Lion: Adversarial distillation of closed-source large language model', 'Tinybert: Distilling bert for natural language understanding', 'Knowledge distillation of large language models'], '2 Literature Review 2.3 Efficient finetuning and inference acceleration': ['Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Medusa: Simple llm inference acceleration framework with multiple decoding heads', 'Loftq: Lora-fine-tuning-aware quantization for large language models', 'Qlora: Efficient finetuning of quantized llms', 'Fast inference from transformers via speculative decoding', 'Adaptive budget allocation for parameter-efficient fine-tuning'], '2 Literature Review 2.4 A breadth of depth-dependent studies': ['Dissecting recall of factual associations in auto-regressive language models', 'Knowledge neurons in pretrained transformers', 'Jump to conclusions: Short-cutting transformers with linear transformations', 'Neurons in large language models: Dead, n-gram, positional', 'Does localization inform editing? surprising differences in causality-based localization vs. knowledge editing in language models', 'Locating and editing factual associations in gpt', 'Task-specific skill localization in fine-tuned language models', 'Eliciting latent predictions from transformers with the tuned lens', 'Interpreting GPT: The Logit Lens', 'Language models represent space and time.'], '4 Results': ['Measuring massive multitask language understanding', 'Llama 2: Open foundation and fine-tuned chat models', 'Mistral 7b', 'Exploring the limits of transfer learning with a unified text-to-text transformer', 'Phi-2: The surprising power of small language models', 'Boolq: Exploring the surprising difficulty of natural yes/no questions', 'Qlora: Efficient finetuning of quantized llms', 'Qwen technical report'], '4 Results 4.2 Loss on next-token predictions': ['Are emergent abilities of large language models a mirage?'], '5 Discussion and Future Directions': ['Lora: Low-rank adaptation of large language models', 'Qlora: Efficient finetuning of quantized llms', 'Llama: Open and efficient foundation language models']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_2', '6567651789981412592']}, {'title': 'Exploring the Performance of Pruning Methods in Neural Networks: An Empirical Study of the Lottery Ticket Hypothesis', 'abstract': ' Abstract In this paper, we explore the performance of different pruning methods in the context of the lottery ticket hypothesis. We compare the performance of L1 unstructured pruning, Fisher pruning, and random pruning on different network architectures and pruning scenarios. The experiments include an evaluation of one-shot and iterative pruning, an examination of weight movement in the network during pruning, a comparison of the pruning methods on networks of varying widths, and an analysis of the performance of the methods when the network becomes very sparse. Additionally, we propose and evaluate a new method for efficient computation of Fisher pruning, known as batched Fisher pruning. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction 1.1 Pruning': ['A simple and effective method for removal of hidden units and weights', 'Optimal Brain Damage'], '1 Introduction 1.2 Pruning methods': ['Faster Gaze Prediction With Dense Networks and Fisher Pruning', 'Optimal Brain Damage', 'Structure learning by pruning in independent component analysis', 'Genetic algorithms and neural networks: optimizing connections and connectivity', 'How to Prune Neural Networks with PyTorch', 'Norm (mathematics)', 'Pruning algorithms of neural networks — a comparative study', 'Two-Phase Construction of Multilayer Perceptrons Using Information Theory', 'Neural Net Pruning — Why and How', 'The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Random Pruning: Return of the Most Naive Baseline for Sparse Training'], '1 Introduction 1.3 Lottery Ticket Hypothesis': ['The lottery tickets hypothesis for supervised and self-supervised pre-training in computer vision models', 'Linear Mode Connectivity and the Lottery Ticket Hypothesis', 'The Lottery Ticket Hypothesis: Finding Sparse, Trainable Neural Networks', 'The Lottery Ticket Hypothesis at Scale', 'Stabilizing the Lottery Ticket Hypothesis', 'Comparing rewinding and fine-tuning in neural network pruning'], '1 Introduction 1.4 Project introduction': ['The Lottery Ticket Hypothesis: Finding Sparse, Trainable Neural Networks', 'Faster Gaze Prediction With Dense Networks and Fisher Pruning', 'The Lottery Ticket Hypothesis at Scale'], '2 Implementation details': ['The Lottery Ticket Hypothesis: Finding Sparse, Trainable Neural Networks', 'Meta Research. OpenLTH: A Framework for Lottery Tickets and Beyond.'], '3 Experiments 3.1 One-shot pruning versus iterative pruning': ['The Lottery Ticket Hypothesis: Finding Sparse, Trainable Neural Networks'], '3 Experiments 3.5 Batched Fisher pruning': ['Speeding up the Hyperparameter Optimization of Deep Convolutional Neural Networks'], '5 Future work': ['Faster Gaze Prediction With Dense Networks and Fisher Pruning']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_0', '2962961071660662589']}, {'title': 'SiPPing Neural Networks: Sensitivity-informed Provable Pruning of Neural Networks', 'abstract': ' Abstract We introduce a family of pruning algorithms that provably sparsifies the parameters of a trained model in a way that approximately preserves the model’s predictive accuracy. Our algorithms use a small batch of input points to construct a data-informed importance sampling distribution over the network’s parameters, and either use a sampling-based or deterministic pruning procedure, or an adaptive mixture thereof, to discard redundant weights. Our pruning methods are simultaneously computationally efficient, provably accurate, and broadly applicable to various network architectures and data distributions. The presented approaches are simple to implement and can be easily integrated into standard prune-retrain pipelines. We present empirical comparisons showing that our algorithms reliably generate highly compressed networks that incur minimal loss in performance relative to that of the original network. ', 'sections': {'1 Introduction': ['Campfire: Compressible, regularization-free, structured sparse training for hardware accelerators', 'Stronger generalization bounds for deep nets via a compression approach', 'Data-dependent coresets for compressing neural networks with applications to generalization bounds', 'Comparing fine-tuning and rewinding in neural network pruning'], '2 Related Work Traditional approaches.': ['Predicting parameters in deep learning', 'Theoretical properties for neural networks with weight matrices of low displacement rank'], '2 Related Work Network pruning.': ['Optimal brain damage', 'Fast convnets using group-wise brain damage', 'Deep compression: Compressing deep neural network with pruning, trained quantization and huffman coding', 'Squeezenet: Alexnet-level accuracy with 50x fewer parameters and< 0.5 mb model size', 'Campfire: Compressible, regularization-free, structured sparse training for hardware accelerators', 'Snip: Single-shot network pruning based on connection sensitivity', 'The state of sparsity in deep neural networks'], '2 Related Work Theoretical foundations.': ['A unified framework for approximating and clustering data', 'Stronger generalization bounds for deep nets via a compression approach', 'Data-dependent coresets for compressing neural networks with applications to generalization bounds'], '4 Method OptAlloc\u200b(θ,ℬ,SS)OptAlloc𝜃ℬSS\\textsc{OptAlloc}(\\theta,\\mathcal{B},\\SS)': ['Improved approximation guarantees for packing and covering integer programs'], '4 Method EmpiricalSensitivity\u200b(θ,SS,i,ℓ)EmpiricalSensitivity𝜃SS𝑖ℓ\\textsc{EmpiricalSensitivity}(\\theta,\\SS,i,\\ell)': ['Data-dependent coresets for compressing neural networks with applications to generalization bounds'], '5 Analysis Error guarantees for SiPPRand': ['High-dimensional probability. An Introduction with Applications'], '5 Analysis Network compression bounds': ['A unified framework for approximating and clustering data', 'Non-linear activations (weighted sum, nonlinearity)', 'Stronger generalization bounds for deep nets via a compression approach'], '6 Experiments': ['Snip: Single-shot network pruning based on connection sensitivity'], '6 Experiments 6.1 Experimental Setup': ['Very deep convolutional networks for large-scale image recognition', 'Wide residual networks', 'Deep double descent: Where bigger models and more data hurt', 'Comparing fine-tuning and rewinding in neural network pruning', 'Deep compression: Compressing deep neural network with pruning, trained quantization and huffman coding', 'Snip: Single-shot network pruning based on connection sensitivity', 'Densely connected convolutional networks', '80 million tiny images: A large data set for nonparametric object and scene recognition', 'ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge', 'Deep residual learning for image recognition'], '6 Experiments 6.2 Iterative prune + retrain': ['Comparing fine-tuning and rewinding in neural network pruning'], '6 Experiments 6.3 Random-init + prune + train': ['Snip: Single-shot network pruning based on connection sensitivity']}, 'source': ['ar5iv_2', '377320067426446980']}]
